00:07:17.630 --> 00:07:21.260
A while back [inaudible]
professor

00:07:21.260 --> 00:07:24.560
of literature interviewed
and asked me apologetically

00:07:24.560 --> 00:07:28.510
if I considered myself to
be an Asian American writer,

00:07:28.510 --> 00:07:31.970
and I didn't understand the
apology, and he explained

00:07:31.970 --> 00:07:35.340
that several of his interviewees
became somewhat in sensed

00:07:35.340 --> 00:07:40.120
at the question, remarking
that they were American writers

00:07:40.120 --> 00:07:42.600
who happened to be
Asian American.

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:46.470
I asked myself, "Where
is Asian America?",

00:07:46.470 --> 00:07:51.230
and what is Asian America if it
is not a political construct?

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:55.770
It is a naming of a category
to recognize the immigration

00:07:55.770 --> 00:07:59.460
and participation of Asia
and Pacific Islander peoples

00:07:59.460 --> 00:08:02.100
in American society
and political life

00:08:02.100 --> 00:08:05.770
over the past 150 years.

00:08:05.770 --> 00:08:08.410
Initially the literature
assorted is grounding

00:08:08.410 --> 00:08:14.290
with in the American Continental
history and geography,

00:08:14.290 --> 00:08:17.310
but it has always been
called referenceable

00:08:17.310 --> 00:08:21.170
to the necessary crossing
of the oceans, both, Pacific

00:08:21.170 --> 00:08:26.550
and Atlantic, without which
it cannot be fully read

00:08:26.550 --> 00:08:28.810
or understood.

00:08:28.810 --> 00:08:30.920
This navigation in
the relationship

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:34.840
to the Americas has not
been necessarily pacific,

00:08:34.840 --> 00:08:37.290
but often a relationship
and result

00:08:37.290 --> 00:08:41.120
of colonialism, racism and war.

00:08:41.120 --> 00:08:43.770
As such, Asian American
literature is at heart,

00:08:43.770 --> 00:08:48.230
a literature of politics
and resistance.

00:08:48.230 --> 00:08:50.030
So, I guess, what I am,

00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:53.510
on apologetically an
Asian American writer.

00:08:53.510 --> 00:09:00.140
[ Applause ]

00:09:00.140 --> 00:09:03.260
So, with that question
out of the way [laughter],

00:09:03.260 --> 00:09:06.890
I want to begin with
what's been asked of me

00:09:06.890 --> 00:09:11.560
on intimate lecture
a way of thinking

00:09:11.560 --> 00:09:15.190
about Asian American
journey, particular to me.

00:09:15.190 --> 00:09:21.180
Of the exact day and year,
I cannot say, but I'm sure

00:09:21.180 --> 00:09:25.330
of that my aunt [inaudible] took
me on a drive form her then,

00:09:25.330 --> 00:09:28.350
home in Rosemont
[inaudible] California,

00:09:28.350 --> 00:09:32.000
to visit my cousin Ted
[inaudible] at his gift shop

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:37.090
on Solano Avenue in Albany,
on the border with Berkeley.

00:09:37.090 --> 00:09:39.880
I'm pretty sure that my aunt
[inaudible] also came along,

00:09:39.880 --> 00:09:44.380
and perhaps we met [inaudible]
wife Barbara at the gift shop.

00:09:44.380 --> 00:09:47.610
The other purpose of that
trip was to climb the steps

00:09:47.610 --> 00:09:50.360
to a small apartment on
the same street to meet

00:09:50.360 --> 00:09:51.660
with the author [inaudible].

00:09:51.660 --> 00:09:55.110
years later I would discover

00:09:55.110 --> 00:09:59.340
in Kate [inaudible] letters her
war time correspondence with one

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:03.680
of her best friends Kate
Uchida, Yoshiko's sister.

00:10:03.680 --> 00:10:06.260
I took for granted
the connection

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:10.870
of the Yamashta family to
the Uchida's connections

00:10:10.870 --> 00:10:13.620
through the church
and UC Berkley

00:10:13.620 --> 00:10:18.550
and to their war-time
incarceration at Topaz in Utah.

00:10:18.550 --> 00:10:21.530
These connections were part
of a tightly net association

00:10:21.530 --> 00:10:23.960
of Japanese immigrant
communities

00:10:23.960 --> 00:10:27.140
in San Francisco
and the East Bay.

00:10:27.140 --> 00:10:30.900
Now, years later, we descendants
can find ourselves tracing the

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:34.940
weave of our relationships
and near encounters.

00:10:34.940 --> 00:10:37.220
Through the Nii Sei
[phonetic] conversation started,

00:10:37.220 --> 00:10:39.720
we often made fun of as kids.

00:10:39.720 --> 00:10:41.920
That conversation
started was always, "hey,

00:10:41.920 --> 00:10:44.440
what camp were you in?"

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:48.050
We thought camp could've
been a tribal event

00:10:48.050 --> 00:10:50.730
of initiation or something.

00:10:50.730 --> 00:10:55.580
Why weren't we sent to camp?

00:10:55.580 --> 00:10:58.340
I realize I can't see.

00:10:58.340 --> 00:11:01.000
I know that choosing K
had planned this meeting

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.080
with Yoshiko Uchida because
they were proud aunties

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:06.230
who thought I was a writer.

00:11:06.230 --> 00:11:09.280
All these years later this
memory is both comical and sweet

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:11.890
to me, and meanwhile
Yoshiko Uchida --

00:11:11.890 --> 00:11:14.000
who met an Ernest Sansey
[phonetic] kids just

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.460
out of college had no idea.

00:11:16.460 --> 00:11:19.940
In those years, Uchida was the
most successfully published

00:11:19.940 --> 00:11:23.110
Japanese American
writer of her generation.

00:11:23.110 --> 00:11:27.850
I might name other Nii
sei writers, Isa Yamamoto,

00:11:27.850 --> 00:11:30.870
Toshio Mori, Wakako
Yamouchi [phonetic],

00:11:30.870 --> 00:11:35.040
Nitsue [phonetic] Yamada but all
these writers only Uchida lived

00:11:35.040 --> 00:11:36.340
by her craft.

00:11:36.340 --> 00:11:38.720
Not that she was
swimming in royalties,

00:11:38.720 --> 00:11:42.310
despite her many published books
she probably received a few

00:11:42.310 --> 00:11:44.550
cents on every copy sold.

00:11:44.550 --> 00:11:47.350
She lived alone and
very modestly.

00:11:47.350 --> 00:11:50.340
She was, I thought,
a real writer.

00:11:50.340 --> 00:11:55.770
I remember asking her why her
stories were not anthologized

00:11:55.770 --> 00:11:59.930
in recent collection's life
I.E. Perhaps there was a hint

00:11:59.930 --> 00:12:01.670
of bitterness in her answer,

00:12:01.670 --> 00:12:05.090
but her audience was
considered juvenile.

00:12:05.090 --> 00:12:07.960
Children's literature had
been a genre form she chosen

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:12.070
to enter the publishing world,
but it was still writing gifted

00:12:12.070 --> 00:12:17.120
with sophistication; years later
she would publish her adult

00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:19.760
memoir, "Desert Exile,
the Uprooting

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:21.500
of a Japanese American Family".

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:25.950
In the 1950s my parents
relocated

00:12:25.950 --> 00:12:28.330
from Oakland to Los Angeles.

00:12:28.330 --> 00:12:30.050
My father, the pastor

00:12:30.050 --> 00:12:34.060
to Japanese American church
Centenary Methodist on 35th

00:12:34.060 --> 00:12:36.270
and Normandy Avenue, my folks

00:12:36.270 --> 00:12:39.980
and other young Nii sei couples
had returned from the war

00:12:39.980 --> 00:12:44.050
and camps to try to jumpstart
their lives in this old center

00:12:44.050 --> 00:12:48.210
of the Japanese American
community in Los Angeles.

00:12:48.210 --> 00:12:51.570
We lived on 5th avenue near
Jefferson, a street line

00:12:51.570 --> 00:12:56.960
with Japanese American
businesses, groceries,

00:12:56.960 --> 00:12:59.410
butcher shops, pharmacies,
dry cleaners,

00:12:59.410 --> 00:13:01.810
candy shops and restaurants.

00:13:01.810 --> 00:13:04.920
Every day my sister and I
walked past these storefronts

00:13:04.920 --> 00:13:07.600
on 6th Avenue elementary school.

00:13:07.600 --> 00:13:10.950
Our classmates and neighbors
were a mix of Japanese

00:13:10.950 --> 00:13:15.250
and African Americans, but
for the most part we lived an

00:13:15.250 --> 00:13:17.510
insular life within the church,

00:13:17.510 --> 00:13:21.530
its Japanese American
congregation and our center.

00:13:21.530 --> 00:13:25.930
In 1949, Uchida published
her first book,

00:13:25.930 --> 00:13:29.600
"The Dancing Tea Kettle" and
other Japanese folk tales.

00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:32.150
I assume that spoke to
have been the first book

00:13:32.150 --> 00:13:34.760
of Japanese folk tales
written in English.

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:38.470
So, we learned to read with
"Dick and Jane" and "Dr. Seuss",

00:13:38.470 --> 00:13:40.970
we also grew up with
Uchida's stories.

00:13:40.970 --> 00:13:44.230
Of these tales the one story
that continues to puzzle

00:13:44.230 --> 00:13:49.840
and resonate for me is
"Urashima Taro [phonetic]".

00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:52.380
Uchida tells the story.

00:13:56.810 --> 00:14:00.940
"Long, long ago, in a
small village of Japan,

00:14:00.940 --> 00:14:04.720
there lived a fine young
man named Urashi Mataro.

00:14:04.720 --> 00:14:06.610
He lived with his
mother and father

00:14:06.610 --> 00:14:10.140
in a thatched grove house,
which over looked the sea.

00:14:10.140 --> 00:14:14.250
Every morning, he was up before
the sun and went out to sea

00:14:14.250 --> 00:14:16.160
in his little fishing boat.

00:14:16.160 --> 00:14:17.990
On the days when
his luck was good,

00:14:17.990 --> 00:14:21.340
he would bring back large
baskets of fish which he sold

00:14:21.340 --> 00:14:24.140
in the village market.

00:14:24.140 --> 00:14:26.290
One day as he was carrying
home his load of fish,

00:14:26.290 --> 00:14:28.310
he saw a group of
shouting children.

00:14:28.310 --> 00:14:30.810
They were gathered around
something on the beach,

00:14:30.810 --> 00:14:33.260
and were crying 'hit
him, poke him'.

00:14:33.260 --> 00:14:35.680
Turned around over to see
what was the matter and then

00:14:35.680 --> 00:14:38.650
on the sand he saw a
big brown tortoise.

00:14:38.650 --> 00:14:40.600
The children were poking
it with a long stick

00:14:40.600 --> 00:14:44.480
and throwing stones
at his hard shell."

00:14:44.480 --> 00:14:46.870
This is how Yoshiko
Uchida's version

00:14:46.870 --> 00:14:49.260
of the Japanese folk
tale begins.

00:14:49.260 --> 00:14:51.620
As the story goes,
Taro saves the tortoise

00:14:51.620 --> 00:14:55.240
from the bullying children,
returning it to the sea.

00:14:55.240 --> 00:14:59.360
"One day while Taro is
fishing, the tortoise appears,

00:14:59.360 --> 00:15:02.030
and as a return gift
of thanks, invites Taro

00:15:02.030 --> 00:15:05.070
to visit the princess
of the sea.

00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:08.790
Taro climbs onto the tortoise's
back and travels to the bottom

00:15:08.790 --> 00:15:12.460
of the sea to see Princess
fed Taro with food and music

00:15:12.460 --> 00:15:16.420
and dancing, in all the
seasons of the year.

00:15:16.420 --> 00:15:21.790
Taro lives in this luxury for
three years, which seems to him

00:15:21.790 --> 00:15:27.800
like three days, but at last
Taro feels he must return home

00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:30.580
to his parents and take
his lead, and as he leaves,

00:15:30.580 --> 00:15:33.710
the princess gives
him a small jewel box,

00:15:33.710 --> 00:15:37.160
stuttered with many precious
stones, and warns him

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:40.470
that if he returns to
the palace of the sea --

00:15:40.470 --> 00:15:44.040
that if he wishes to return
to the palace of the sea,

00:15:44.040 --> 00:15:47.750
he must never open that box".

00:15:47.750 --> 00:15:51.880
Well, perhaps anyway,
you know the story.

00:15:53.370 --> 00:15:56.990
Sometime after the Watts
riot and the assassination

00:15:56.990 --> 00:15:59.880
of John F. Kennedy, and
after my father's stroke

00:15:59.880 --> 00:16:04.600
and disability retirement,
my family moved to Gardena,

00:16:04.600 --> 00:16:07.770
an old on-clay but
Japanese American strawberry

00:16:07.770 --> 00:16:13.430
and flower farmers, turning
their land into the suburbs.

00:16:13.430 --> 00:16:16.690
By then I was in high school
and cynical enough to agree

00:16:16.690 --> 00:16:24.040
with my friends that Gardena
was the armpit of America.

00:16:24.040 --> 00:16:25.830
This brings me to speak of a few

00:16:25.830 --> 00:16:31.240
of my Gardena high
school friends --

00:16:31.240 --> 00:16:37.290
in particular, Kathy Yamamoto
and Garret Hunkle [phonetic].

00:16:37.290 --> 00:16:39.790
Kathy was always writing,
she was the editor

00:16:39.790 --> 00:16:42.990
of the school newspaper, but
before that she was the editor

00:16:42.990 --> 00:16:45.590
of a fan letter for the Beatles.

00:16:45.590 --> 00:16:51.540
I figured Kathy was a writer
because it was in her genes.

00:16:51.540 --> 00:16:53.850
Her aunt was Hisaya
[phonetic] Yamamoto

00:16:53.850 --> 00:16:56.730
and Hisaya's best friend
was Wakako Yamouchi,

00:16:56.730 --> 00:17:00.180
who also lived in Gardena.

00:17:00.180 --> 00:17:03.420
Like the relationship of
my aunts to Yochiko Uchida,

00:17:03.420 --> 00:17:06.430
I never paid much attention
to Kathy's relationship

00:17:06.430 --> 00:17:09.630
with these two illustrious
Nii-sei writers.

00:17:09.630 --> 00:17:12.240
Some years after high school
I heard Garret complained

00:17:12.240 --> 00:17:17.110
to Kathy, why hadn't she told
him about Hisaya and Wakako?

00:17:17.110 --> 00:17:21.370
Introduced in sooner when
we were in high school.

00:17:21.370 --> 00:17:24.710
Kathy replied with
amusement, "Garrett,

00:17:24.710 --> 00:17:28.620
I didn't know you wanted
to become a writer.

00:17:28.620 --> 00:17:38.920
Hey, I thought you wanted
to blow up the world."

00:17:40.290 --> 00:17:44.100
He did. One Gardena
summer, Garrett lived

00:17:44.100 --> 00:17:46.420
in an apartment block,
a block away

00:17:46.420 --> 00:17:49.550
from Wakako Yamomuchi's
house, walking back and forth

00:17:49.550 --> 00:17:53.190
and forming a mentoring
and writer relationship

00:17:53.190 --> 00:17:55.220
that has lasted a lifetime.

00:17:55.220 --> 00:18:00.550
In 1982, Garrett published
this poem for Wakako Yamomuchi,

00:18:00.550 --> 00:18:03.890
in his first book of poetry
Yabbo light [phonetic].

00:18:03.890 --> 00:18:08.380
The title to the poem is
"And your soul shall dance",

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:12.740
honoring Wakako's short story,
a story she eventually crafted

00:18:12.740 --> 00:18:19.000
into the dramatic
play by the same name.

00:18:20.320 --> 00:18:24.660
"Walking to school beside fields
of tomatoes and summer squash,

00:18:24.660 --> 00:18:28.090
alone and humming a
Japanese love song,

00:18:28.090 --> 00:18:29.890
you've concealed a
copy of photoplay

00:18:29.890 --> 00:18:32.870
between your Algebra
and English texts.

00:18:32.870 --> 00:18:36.330
Your Niisak [phonetic] saddle
shoes, plaid dress and blouse,

00:18:36.330 --> 00:18:40.770
long sleeved in white, with
ruffles down the front,

00:18:40.770 --> 00:18:42.660
come from a Sears catalogue

00:18:42.660 --> 00:18:47.480
and neatly complement
your new tony curls.

00:18:47.480 --> 00:18:50.790
All of this sets you
apart from the landscape,

00:18:50.790 --> 00:18:53.870
flat valley grooved
with irrigation dishes

00:18:53.870 --> 00:18:57.960
of tractor grinding
through alkaline earth.

00:18:57.960 --> 00:19:00.850
The short stands of
windbreak eucalyptus,

00:19:00.850 --> 00:19:04.470
shuttering the dessert
wind from a small cluster

00:19:04.470 --> 00:19:08.710
of wooden tracks, where
your mother hangs the wash".

00:19:08.710 --> 00:19:11.870
"You want to go somewhere,
somewhere far away

00:19:11.870 --> 00:19:17.030
from all the dust and swerving
machines and acres of lettuce,

00:19:17.030 --> 00:19:20.480
somewhere where you might
be kissed by someone

00:19:20.480 --> 00:19:23.560
with smooth, artistic hands.

00:19:23.560 --> 00:19:27.270
When you turn into the
schoolyard, the flag pole gleans

00:19:27.270 --> 00:19:31.870
like a knife blade in the
sun, and classmates scatter

00:19:31.870 --> 00:19:38.200
like chickens, shoed by the
storm brooding in your horizon".

00:19:39.890 --> 00:19:44.070
I believe that what Garrett
captures here is the same desire

00:19:44.070 --> 00:19:48.070
both he and I shared for
something beyond the confinement

00:19:48.070 --> 00:19:51.910
of our provincial
roots and origins,

00:19:51.910 --> 00:19:54.970
even though we would
have to return again

00:19:54.970 --> 00:19:59.280
and again in order to leave.

00:19:59.280 --> 00:20:03.020
Leading the old armpit
of my California home,

00:20:03.020 --> 00:20:06.090
I went to school in
Minnesota, Carlton College,

00:20:06.090 --> 00:20:08.940
and one day Alex Hayley, the
author of the autobiography

00:20:08.940 --> 00:20:12.820
of Malcolm X, arrive to give
the convocation lecture.

00:20:12.820 --> 00:20:15.410
Though it seems an
impossible memory,

00:20:15.410 --> 00:20:18.960
I believe we were riveted to our
seats for the next three ours,

00:20:18.960 --> 00:20:21.750
while Hayley spoke of his
relationship in writing

00:20:21.750 --> 00:20:24.730
with Malcolm X. in
the first hour,

00:20:24.730 --> 00:20:28.410
and then for the next two hours
he told decadent storytelling

00:20:28.410 --> 00:20:30.380
of the transatlantic crossing

00:20:30.380 --> 00:20:34.320
of his named ancestor
Kunta Kinte [phonetic].

00:20:34.320 --> 00:20:36.500
I've never forgotten
that day sitting

00:20:36.500 --> 00:20:40.690
up in the Skinner Memorial
Chapel filled to capacity.

00:20:40.690 --> 00:20:45.410
That we came and come from
somewhere had meaning.

00:20:45.410 --> 00:20:50.320
In the next few I will take
my transpacific crossing

00:20:50.320 --> 00:20:56.170
to do what my family
called "Katie's root swing".

00:20:56.170 --> 00:20:59.510
Figure out where we came
from and why but finding

00:20:59.510 --> 00:21:01.640
out my roots turned
out to be a mixed bag

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:04.030
because I had thought it
would be the same thing

00:21:04.030 --> 00:21:06.290
as finding belonging.

00:21:06.290 --> 00:21:08.570
If I had not entirely belonged

00:21:08.570 --> 00:21:13.230
to my Japanese American
communities in LA and Gardena,

00:21:13.230 --> 00:21:17.010
I was a really bad fit in Japan.

00:21:18.280 --> 00:21:20.580
In my continued years
at Carlton,

00:21:20.580 --> 00:21:23.390
two professors there
were special mentors,

00:21:23.390 --> 00:21:26.310
American literature
professor Bob Tisdale

00:21:26.310 --> 00:21:29.150
and anthropologist Paul Riesman.

00:21:29.150 --> 00:21:31.940
Many years later I
realized that it was Tisdale

00:21:31.940 --> 00:21:36.250
who quietly believed in me,
despite my huge anxieties.

00:21:36.250 --> 00:21:40.670
He was behind small invitations
to meet writers at his home

00:21:40.670 --> 00:21:43.820
and supported my proposal
for the Watson fellowship,

00:21:43.820 --> 00:21:46.000
that would send me to Brazil.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:49.270
And it was Paul Riesman who
made me understand my role

00:21:49.270 --> 00:21:53.320
as a stranger, in the powers
of observation, empathy,

00:21:53.320 --> 00:21:55.520
that role might support.

00:21:55.520 --> 00:22:00.750
The lessons my teachers provided
took many years to understand.

00:22:00.750 --> 00:22:09.500
I was sent away with two odd and
desperate but now obvious books.

00:22:09.500 --> 00:22:12.690
Claude Levi Strauss'
"Tristes Tropiques"

00:22:12.690 --> 00:22:16.680
and Gabriel Garcia Marquez's
"100 years of solitude",

00:22:16.680 --> 00:22:18.700
and I would have to
travel to the other side

00:22:18.700 --> 00:22:21.830
of the hemisphere, a
time travel of sorts,

00:22:21.830 --> 00:22:24.320
to meet another community
of Japanese immigrants

00:22:24.320 --> 00:22:27.070
who had acculturated Brazilian.

00:22:27.070 --> 00:22:30.000
If these Japanese
immigrants were Brazilian,

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:33.980
what did it mean to be American?

00:22:33.980 --> 00:22:38.090
This is the question I pondered
while researching the Japanese

00:22:38.090 --> 00:22:40.190
Brazilian community and writing

00:22:40.190 --> 00:22:43.250
and rewriting the novel
Brazil Modu [phonetic].

00:22:43.250 --> 00:22:46.990
I arrived in Brazil at the
end of the American 60s,

00:22:46.990 --> 00:22:52.700
a period ripe with ideological,
racial and political turmoil,

00:22:52.700 --> 00:22:55.170
the Vietnam War,
hippie communalism

00:22:55.170 --> 00:22:57.520
and civil rights movements.

00:22:57.520 --> 00:23:00.460
I met a community of
Japanese Brazilians who lived

00:23:00.460 --> 00:23:04.550
through similar experiments,
idealizing a new civilization

00:23:04.550 --> 00:23:08.410
and practicing communalism
from the 1920s on.

00:23:08.410 --> 00:23:12.530
These people could've been my
grandparents -- my parents.

00:23:12.530 --> 00:23:14.160
What had happened
to their community

00:23:14.160 --> 00:23:17.150
and how did they
survive the war years?

00:23:17.150 --> 00:23:22.620
What I learned were dozens of
resilience, hubris and failure.

00:23:22.620 --> 00:23:26.700
Over the many years since
I've maintained interest

00:23:26.700 --> 00:23:30.440
in scholarship and writing
about Asians in the Americas,

00:23:30.440 --> 00:23:34.570
I've only recently come across
maybe Asian American writing

00:23:34.570 --> 00:23:37.740
that haunts the psyche
of Brazilian discovery.

00:23:37.740 --> 00:23:41.920
Encounters of the indigenous and
civilized science and belief,

00:23:41.920 --> 00:23:45.110
sexuality and race
story and history,

00:23:45.110 --> 00:23:47.670
and while her story
resides in the pacific,

00:23:47.670 --> 00:23:50.390
in her novel "The
people in the trees",

00:23:50.390 --> 00:23:53.300
Hanya Yanagihara [phonetic]
binned these narratives

00:23:53.300 --> 00:23:56.940
in her writing with
complexity and danger.

00:23:56.940 --> 00:24:00.350
This segment from "The people
in the trees" reminds me

00:24:00.350 --> 00:24:04.080
of the folk tale
of Hurashima Taro,

00:24:04.080 --> 00:24:06.880
which kindly extends
darkly and magically

00:24:06.880 --> 00:24:10.810
to explore ideas of immortality.

00:24:18.070 --> 00:24:21.130
"As my father stood
near the shore very sad,

00:24:21.130 --> 00:24:23.690
he suddenly saw something
sliding beneath the

00:24:23.690 --> 00:24:25.340
water surface.

00:24:25.340 --> 00:24:28.680
To my father's great
astonishment, the thing rose,

00:24:28.680 --> 00:24:31.740
and my father saw that it
was an enormous turtle --

00:24:31.740 --> 00:24:34.590
the biggest he had ever seen.

00:24:34.590 --> 00:24:36.620
Both taller and wider
than he was,

00:24:36.620 --> 00:24:40.440
its fetus large has law-wide
spurs, paddling the water

00:24:40.440 --> 00:24:43.860
in brisk, forcible strokes,
and staring at my father

00:24:43.860 --> 00:24:46.750
with its slow, yellow eyes.

00:24:46.750 --> 00:24:51.040
My father was so amazed he
found himself unable to move.

00:24:51.040 --> 00:24:55.400
But then the turtle waggled the
top half of its body to the lent

00:24:55.400 --> 00:24:57.480
and my father understood
that he was

00:24:57.480 --> 00:25:00.940
to straddle the turtle's back
and the turtle will take him

00:25:00.940 --> 00:25:02.830
to Ibu-Ibu" [phonetic].

00:25:02.830 --> 00:25:04.940
"My father had never
felt exhilaration

00:25:04.940 --> 00:25:08.010
like the kind he experienced
riding on top of the turtle.

00:25:08.010 --> 00:25:10.630
The turtle swam gingerly
through the shallows,

00:25:10.630 --> 00:25:13.720
careful not to scratch his feet
on the great oceans of coral.

00:25:13.720 --> 00:25:17.060
But once they were in open
water, his swimming became swift

00:25:17.060 --> 00:25:20.710
and powerful, and they passed
coups of sharks, pots of whales

00:25:20.710 --> 00:25:25.540
and once that magnificent flee
of other opaiba icas [phonetic].

00:25:25.540 --> 00:25:29.310
Hundreds of them, he just
did, as the one he was riding,

00:25:29.310 --> 00:25:32.290
who lifted their heads from
the water and stared at him,

00:25:32.290 --> 00:25:37.830
as if in salute, with the
multiplicity of glowing eyes".

00:25:37.830 --> 00:25:41.370
Hara captures here the idea
of the turtle as a magical

00:25:41.370 --> 00:25:45.760
but also an inscrutable being
upon whose back we climb hoping

00:25:45.760 --> 00:25:47.960
to find our destiny.

00:25:47.960 --> 00:25:52.270
Perhaps what lies ahead is
an adventure or an escape,

00:25:52.270 --> 00:25:55.200
or the moment of our death.

00:25:55.200 --> 00:25:58.730
The turtle is the great
vehicle, on silence they ship.

00:25:58.730 --> 00:26:00.350
The responsibility

00:26:00.350 --> 00:26:06.110
of our journey is only
our own, real or imagined.

00:26:07.370 --> 00:26:10.710
About the time that the
Brazilian government --

00:26:10.710 --> 00:26:12.660
or military returned
the government

00:26:12.660 --> 00:26:16.630
to a civilian democracy, I
left with my Brazilian family

00:26:16.630 --> 00:26:19.500
to immigrate into Los Angeles.

00:26:19.500 --> 00:26:23.540
As predicted, LA had become a
diversely cosmopolitan city,

00:26:23.540 --> 00:26:26.550
it's growing majority
complexion turned Latino.

00:26:26.550 --> 00:26:31.020
And by the time the 1992 riots
burned across our landscape,

00:26:31.020 --> 00:26:34.770
we knew the media had completely
mischaracterized the conflicts

00:26:34.770 --> 00:26:38.010
as black and white
or black and Korean.

00:26:38.010 --> 00:26:41.540
As Brazilians, we were part
of the Latin American shift,

00:26:41.540 --> 00:26:43.370
and I saw to understand
that shift

00:26:43.370 --> 00:26:45.660
in a novel called
"Tropic of Orange".

00:26:45.660 --> 00:26:48.050
It was during this time
that I met and have ever

00:26:48.050 --> 00:26:51.560
since been inspired by
the east LA poet Sesshu

00:26:51.560 --> 00:26:53.690
[phonetic] Foster.

00:26:53.690 --> 00:26:58.020
Sesshu narrates as only Sesshu
can an alternative reality

00:26:58.020 --> 00:27:02.230
in his non-novel
"Atomic Aztec" --

00:27:02.230 --> 00:27:06.930
I'd better drink another glass.

00:27:06.930 --> 00:27:11.670
"Perhaps you are
familiar with this --

00:27:11.670 --> 00:27:15.830
with some world stupider
realities among an alternative

00:27:15.830 --> 00:27:19.200
universe is in which the Aztec
civilization was destroyed.

00:27:19.200 --> 00:27:21.400
That's the possibility --

00:27:21.400 --> 00:27:23.540
I mean, that's what the
Europeans thought they planned,

00:27:23.540 --> 00:27:26.620
genocide, wipe out our
civilization, build cathedrals

00:27:26.620 --> 00:27:29.200
on top of our pyramids,
hump our women --

00:27:29.200 --> 00:27:31.870
not just our women but
analyst people, designate them

00:27:31.870 --> 00:27:34.220
with small postesels
[phonetic] and shit pits.

00:27:34.220 --> 00:27:36.740
Welfare lines, workaholism
[phonetic], imbecility

00:27:36.740 --> 00:27:40.180
and slave them into silver
minds and Potosi, the gold minds

00:27:40.180 --> 00:27:44.030
in El Dorado and Disneylandia
[phonetic], on golf courses

00:27:44.030 --> 00:27:46.330
and country clubs --
chingados [phonetic].

00:27:46.330 --> 00:27:49.550
All our brothers --
you get the picture".

00:27:49.550 --> 00:27:52.250
"The European figure,
they wipe us out.

00:27:52.250 --> 00:27:54.490
Planee [phonetic]
and slave our people

00:27:54.490 --> 00:27:57.070
down at Tacoma Liquor
Store, crush our resistance,

00:27:57.070 --> 00:27:59.750
then claim it was
all an accident.

00:27:59.750 --> 00:28:03.450
Just their luck, they pretend
they just happen on their way

00:28:03.450 --> 00:28:06.800
to India to buy some carom
and some nutmeg and spice;

00:28:06.800 --> 00:28:13.790
like you just accidently happen
to designate whole civilizations

00:28:13.790 --> 00:28:16.500
and worlds just to set a
nice breakfast table --

00:28:16.500 --> 00:28:20.350
hot coffee, cinnamon
toast, Chinese silverware.

00:28:20.350 --> 00:28:22.560
Did we care if they
had a plan B?

00:28:22.560 --> 00:28:25.650
Hell no, because in no way
does this fit our aesthetic

00:28:25.650 --> 00:28:29.210
conception of how the
universe is supposed to run.

00:28:29.210 --> 00:28:30.670
It's just plain ugly.

00:28:30.670 --> 00:28:33.890
The Spanish believed they
had superior fire powder --

00:28:33.890 --> 00:28:38.690
gun powder, crossbows, steel,
armor body, Arabian horses,

00:28:38.690 --> 00:28:39.990
gallions built on convoys".

00:28:39.990 --> 00:28:44.700
"All this was true, but we asked
to have our ways and means,

00:28:44.700 --> 00:28:47.220
we have access to the
meanest, nastiest,

00:28:47.220 --> 00:28:49.540
psycho [inaudible] voodoo.

00:28:49.540 --> 00:28:55.470
Jump blues, human sacrifices,
proletarian fam guard parties.

00:28:55.470 --> 00:29:00.720
Angry coffee house, poetry,
fantasy life intensified

00:29:00.720 --> 00:29:05.510
by the masturbation and comic
books on all our armies,

00:29:05.510 --> 00:29:07.940
flower warriors,
jaguar legions, jujitsu

00:29:07.940 --> 00:29:09.930
and of course, the
secret weapon.

00:29:09.930 --> 00:29:16.010
In a nutshell, the Spanish
didn't have a chance".

00:29:16.010 --> 00:29:19.270
The imagination sometimes
revealed itself intensely

00:29:19.270 --> 00:29:23.300
and vibrantly insane,
but it's only sane --

00:29:23.300 --> 00:29:26.220
but it's the only sane
sight where we can do war.

00:29:26.220 --> 00:29:30.000
Bloody hand to hand combat,
express grief and anger

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:33.670
and find solace and
reconciliation.

00:29:33.670 --> 00:29:38.830
In the mid-90s I met Ryuta
Imafuku [phonetic] writers color

00:29:38.830 --> 00:29:41.300
and cultural critic, who invited

00:29:41.300 --> 00:29:43.890
and sponsored my family
a six-month stay in Japan

00:29:43.890 --> 00:29:46.560
to research the return migration

00:29:46.560 --> 00:29:49.500
of Japanese Brazilian
factory labors.

00:29:49.500 --> 00:29:52.710
During that period,
Ryuta invited me

00:29:52.710 --> 00:29:55.580
to write online monthly
installments

00:29:55.580 --> 00:29:57.970
about anatomy search
and travels,

00:29:57.970 --> 00:30:02.060
and those essays found their
way into circle case cycles.

00:30:02.060 --> 00:30:05.770
It was Ryuta's insistent
but always gentile prodding

00:30:05.770 --> 00:30:07.660
that encouraged me to see

00:30:07.660 --> 00:30:10.810
and explore the growing
Brazilian Dekasegi [phonetic]

00:30:10.810 --> 00:30:14.220
community and to see that
community in despotic movement,

00:30:14.220 --> 00:30:18.910
in the context of both
historic and contemporary japan.

00:30:18.910 --> 00:30:23.260
If I had learned my lesson, as
a young stranger in years past,

00:30:23.260 --> 00:30:28.990
I was given the confidence and
freedom of an old stranger.

00:30:28.990 --> 00:30:32.610
The twisting triangulations of
my world are constantly changing

00:30:32.610 --> 00:30:36.040
and flexible, although it's
possible to name other writers

00:30:36.040 --> 00:30:39.450
who live with such
mobility, I feel closest

00:30:39.450 --> 00:30:43.700
to the shifting homes of
Arizamora Linmap[phonetic] mark,

00:30:43.700 --> 00:30:48.050
moving about from Honolulu
to Manila to San Francisco,

00:30:48.050 --> 00:30:50.530
to Miami, Madrid, Buenos Aires,

00:30:50.530 --> 00:30:54.450
Tokyo and all these pursuing
the chaos of language

00:30:54.450 --> 00:30:57.240
with clay and dark humor.

00:30:57.240 --> 00:30:59.780
"A recurrent immigrant story is

00:30:59.780 --> 00:31:02.540
that laborists leave
their children behind

00:31:02.540 --> 00:31:05.500
with grandparents or
relatives and then send

00:31:05.500 --> 00:31:07.400
for their children years later,

00:31:07.400 --> 00:31:09.980
when they are able
to afford to do so.

00:31:09.980 --> 00:31:13.580
This is the last scene
of Zack's novel "Leche".

00:31:13.580 --> 00:31:17.000
The protagonist, Vince
returns from Kalili [phonetic],

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:22.420
Honolulu to his childhood home
in the Philippines, San Vicente,

00:31:22.420 --> 00:31:26.530
where his grandfather has
died to find the empty

00:31:26.530 --> 00:31:30.620
of his family and
childhood passed.

00:31:31.710 --> 00:31:36.030
In the photograph, what happened
to the wall to wall photographs

00:31:36.030 --> 00:31:40.190
that show generation after
generation of the Lewis clan?

00:31:40.190 --> 00:31:42.430
Where are the hand
painted photographs of turn

00:31:42.430 --> 00:31:45.570
of the century relatives,
one who came to the tropics

00:31:45.570 --> 00:31:47.970
as a soldier to fight
the Philippinos

00:31:47.970 --> 00:31:49.690
and another to teach them?

00:31:49.690 --> 00:31:54.090
And the airport group shots
of himself, Alvin, Gene,

00:31:54.090 --> 00:31:57.660
Yaya Leti [phonetic] and Don
Alfonso in front of the fountain

00:31:57.660 --> 00:32:02.040
on the afternoon, they were
sent off to their parents.

00:32:02.040 --> 00:32:04.760
Whom do they belong to now?"

00:32:04.760 --> 00:32:08.630
"He reassures himself
that they're upstairs

00:32:08.630 --> 00:32:11.280
where the bedrooms are, the
runs up the wooden staircase,

00:32:11.280 --> 00:32:12.580
head straight forward
to the room

00:32:12.580 --> 00:32:15.620
as if he lived there all his
life -- it too was empty,

00:32:15.620 --> 00:32:18.890
as empty as the succession
of closets

00:32:18.890 --> 00:32:22.300
and cabinet drawers he pulls
open, hoping to get assaulted

00:32:22.300 --> 00:32:25.940
by memorabilia, smelling
of moss balls, but nothing.

00:32:25.940 --> 00:32:31.450
No one dusty shelf of books
or issue of comics -- empty".

00:32:31.450 --> 00:32:33.910
"Fighting off tears and with
a heart that doesn't know

00:32:33.910 --> 00:32:36.840
when to give up hope, he
searches room after room,

00:32:36.840 --> 00:32:40.370
wall after wall, for halls
punctured by nails upon

00:32:40.370 --> 00:32:42.350
which used to hang the guilt

00:32:42.350 --> 00:32:47.660
and picture frames he checks
the inside of doors for shadows

00:32:47.660 --> 00:32:51.490
of the photographs that
had once been tacked there.

00:32:51.490 --> 00:32:56.540
He took everything with him, to
his grave -- he tells himself,

00:32:56.540 --> 00:32:59.970
he didn't want me to return
and reclaim what was mine.

00:32:59.970 --> 00:33:05.320
My family history, objects from
my childhood, nothing salvage,

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:12.110
nothing, except this house,
smelling of mule waxed floors".

00:33:14.190 --> 00:33:15.920
Zack mourns here the loss

00:33:15.920 --> 00:33:19.490
of home while showing the
predicament of mobility

00:33:19.490 --> 00:33:24.650
of the transnational, as a stage
of new, global citizenship,

00:33:24.650 --> 00:33:29.070
often celebrated but also
for many, migrant labors,

00:33:29.070 --> 00:33:32.420
a state in limbo, and
great precarity [phonetic].

00:33:32.420 --> 00:33:35.750
So, it seems that here the
great turtle with its shell

00:33:35.750 --> 00:33:38.620
as home has a different lesson.

00:33:38.620 --> 00:33:42.930
How we must also travel within
our bodies, even if marked

00:33:42.930 --> 00:33:46.230
by ethnicity, gender and color.

00:33:56.040 --> 00:33:58.500
In the late 90s I began
teaching at UC Santa Cruz.

00:33:58.500 --> 00:34:02.250
And along with learning
how to teach I made forays,

00:34:02.250 --> 00:34:05.320
into San Francisco to research
the Asian American movement

00:34:05.320 --> 00:34:10.530
as it is was birth in Chinatown,
Manila Town, Japan Town

00:34:10.530 --> 00:34:13.810
and then the universities,
the factories, culture

00:34:13.810 --> 00:34:17.980
and political institutions
spawned in that period.

00:34:17.980 --> 00:34:19.280
And I would have found --

00:34:19.280 --> 00:34:21.600
and I found the center
of that narrative

00:34:21.600 --> 00:34:25.490
in the international
or the I-Hotel.

00:34:25.490 --> 00:34:30.460
As with other projects, I sat
out to be a gathering machine,

00:34:30.460 --> 00:34:34.710
recording Marriott stories of
anyone willing to talk to me.

00:34:34.710 --> 00:34:39.020
I never recorded anyone
on a recording machine.

00:34:39.020 --> 00:34:43.780
My method has been to record
with my body, and to remember,

00:34:43.780 --> 00:34:47.970
well, everything, bodily
expression, insinuations,

00:34:47.970 --> 00:34:50.990
syntax, cadence and story.

00:34:50.990 --> 00:34:57.800
The most difficult recording was
the one I tried to accomplish

00:34:57.800 --> 00:35:01.040
with the poet Al Robles.

00:35:01.040 --> 00:35:03.710
I met with him at Vesuvian
[phonetic] North Beach next

00:35:03.710 --> 00:35:08.110
to city lights and sit
close with him for hours,

00:35:08.110 --> 00:35:11.770
while I tried to pin down the
most preposterous stories.

00:35:11.770 --> 00:35:16.350
By the time they grew dark, he
stood up and said, "hey Karen,

00:35:16.350 --> 00:35:20.250
let's get some dirty food",
which meant that we would go

00:35:20.250 --> 00:35:25.680
to Chinatown and slip into a
greasy diner for chop suey.

00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:29.320
I think I dropped him off
at home around midnight

00:35:29.320 --> 00:35:30.850
and headed back to Santa Cruz.

00:35:30.850 --> 00:35:36.100
I was exhausted, I've been
recording from maybe 12 hours,

00:35:36.100 --> 00:35:40.020
maybe I didn't get Al's
stories right, but he was,

00:35:40.020 --> 00:35:42.330
as his friend said, the
poet Monka [phonetic]

00:35:42.330 --> 00:35:47.430
that tendered a loin
and I miss him dearly.

00:35:47.430 --> 00:35:49.320
Al with the help of
Roselian [phonetic]

00:35:49.320 --> 00:35:52.010
at the UCLA Asian
American studies center,

00:35:52.010 --> 00:35:56.220
published one book of poetry,
"Wraping with 10,000 caravans

00:35:56.220 --> 00:35:58.680
in the dark" and this
is the first stanza

00:35:58.680 --> 00:36:01.790
of that signature poem.

00:36:01.790 --> 00:36:05.690
"International hotel in the
Mongol heart in east the mind

00:36:05.690 --> 00:36:09.430
of the Philippines where old
and young Philippinos live,

00:36:09.430 --> 00:36:12.820
hang and roam around on
daylight cutouts in the mud.

00:36:12.820 --> 00:36:16.360
Eating, sleeping and working,
Philippinos scattered all over,

00:36:16.360 --> 00:36:19.960
brown faces pile high,
moving like shadows on trees,

00:36:19.960 --> 00:36:23.540
concrete doorways, poohas
[phonetic], barber shops.

00:36:23.540 --> 00:36:25.960
Guitar music echoes
through down deep

00:36:25.960 --> 00:36:29.330
in your Mongol heart
and ease their mind.

00:36:29.330 --> 00:36:34.280
Chinatown across the way, 60,000
or more live in rooms the size

00:36:34.280 --> 00:36:38.170
of tea pots, searching,
stretching east,

00:36:38.170 --> 00:36:40.070
west, north and south.

00:36:40.070 --> 00:36:43.560
Thousands are crammed in damp
basements, alleyways behind,

00:36:43.560 --> 00:36:47.500
run down barrels of ancient
Chinese mountain wine,

00:36:47.500 --> 00:36:51.850
thousands of Chinese children
run, soy sauce streets,

00:36:51.850 --> 00:36:55.380
long black-haired
listening like a cool stream

00:36:55.380 --> 00:36:58.060
of quiet moon watches".

00:36:58.060 --> 00:37:01.630
"Short crop of hair,
morning spring faces,

00:37:01.630 --> 00:37:04.600
underneath fresh soaked clouds;

00:37:04.600 --> 00:37:11.580
all those tiny footsteps
keep the winter valley warm.

00:37:11.580 --> 00:37:14.310
Similar to the turtle algae,

00:37:14.310 --> 00:37:17.580
the old Philippino
batches the Mongol are kind

00:37:17.580 --> 00:37:20.190
of mythical stages as cut about.

00:37:20.190 --> 00:37:23.690
Watcher buffalo, roaming
so rarely in the halls

00:37:23.690 --> 00:37:27.090
and teapot rooms of the
international hotel,

00:37:27.090 --> 00:37:29.410
mud replaced by concrete
doorways,

00:37:29.410 --> 00:37:33.210
barbershops poohas,
soy sauce streets".

00:37:33.210 --> 00:37:36.290
In the past years I've
been forced to think

00:37:36.290 --> 00:37:40.200
about the future, probably
because many of my students want

00:37:40.200 --> 00:37:43.130
to write science
fiction and fantasy.

00:37:43.130 --> 00:37:46.820
What the academy has
rebranded as speculative.

00:37:46.820 --> 00:37:50.060
My colleague Nika
[phonetic] Perks pointed

00:37:50.060 --> 00:37:52.810
out that I've been a
speculative writer for years,

00:37:52.810 --> 00:37:55.240
I just didn't know
it, and with the help

00:37:55.240 --> 00:37:58.960
of Steven Honsong [phonetic]
I published "Anime Wong",

00:37:58.960 --> 00:38:01.250
fictions of performance.

00:38:01.250 --> 00:38:03.980
This work remembers
my collaborations

00:38:03.980 --> 00:38:07.770
with director Sushiko
Hoshi, ideographer,

00:38:07.770 --> 00:38:09.710
Karamaeda [phonetic]
and composers

00:38:09.710 --> 00:38:13.290
that kept Beabe [phonetic]
and Glen Horiuchi [phonetic].

00:38:13.290 --> 00:38:15.630
And the dozens of actors,
dancers, designers,

00:38:15.630 --> 00:38:18.080
stage personnel and producers

00:38:18.080 --> 00:38:22.120
who joined our performance
projects presented at venues

00:38:22.120 --> 00:38:25.800
in Los Angeles for Asian
American audiences.

00:38:27.260 --> 00:38:30.550
Recently, more Asian American
writers have taken a turn

00:38:30.550 --> 00:38:32.740
to the speculative,
and I have followed

00:38:32.740 --> 00:38:35.450
with admiration the
work of Chang Ray Lee

00:38:35.450 --> 00:38:38.930
since his book "Native Speaker".

00:38:38.930 --> 00:38:40.870
Most recently his novel "On

00:38:40.870 --> 00:38:44.540
such a fool sea" imagines
the present future of vacated

00:38:44.540 --> 00:38:48.010
and bided cities and the
global exchange of labor

00:38:48.010 --> 00:38:53.910
in a completely secular society,
governed by class and capital.

00:38:53.910 --> 00:38:56.580
What follows are
edited selections

00:38:56.580 --> 00:39:01.420
that introduce the collective
narrator are the protagonists

00:39:01.420 --> 00:39:03.950
of Chang Ray's novel.

00:39:11.340 --> 00:39:15.760
"It is known where we came from,
it is known where we come from,

00:39:15.760 --> 00:39:18.810
but no one much cares
about these things,

00:39:18.810 --> 00:39:21.770
but things like that anymore.

00:39:21.770 --> 00:39:23.870
We think 'why bother?'

00:39:23.870 --> 00:39:27.790
Except for a lucky few,
everyone is from some place

00:39:27.790 --> 00:39:31.610
but that some place
it turns out is gone.

00:39:31.610 --> 00:39:34.200
You can search it, you
can find pits or bits

00:39:34.200 --> 00:39:37.600
that show what the
place last looked like.

00:39:37.600 --> 00:39:40.310
In our case they
gavel color shop town

00:39:40.310 --> 00:39:44.890
of stoop shouldered buildings
on a river bank in china,

00:39:44.890 --> 00:39:47.870
shore hills in the
distance, rooftops

00:39:47.870 --> 00:39:50.590
and nests of wires and junk.

00:39:50.590 --> 00:39:54.120
The river tea still,
a swath of black,

00:39:54.120 --> 00:39:57.630
and blunting it all is a
haze you can almost smell,

00:39:57.630 --> 00:40:01.800
a smell you think you
don't want to breathe in".

00:40:01.800 --> 00:40:05.270
"So, what does it matter if
the town was raised one day?

00:40:05.270 --> 00:40:07.290
After our people were
truffed [phonetic] out,

00:40:07.290 --> 00:40:08.870
what difference does it make

00:40:08.870 --> 00:40:11.040
that there's almost
nothing there now?

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:13.370
It was on the other
side of the world,

00:40:13.370 --> 00:40:16.720
which might as well be
a light year away --

00:40:16.720 --> 00:40:20.400
though probably it was mourned
when they were thriving.

00:40:20.400 --> 00:40:24.280
People are funny that way,
even the most miserable kind

00:40:24.280 --> 00:40:30.140
of circumstance can inspire
a genuine throb of nostalgia.

00:40:30.140 --> 00:40:33.210
And then there is
the tale of Fan,

00:40:33.210 --> 00:40:35.720
a young woman whose
cause has been taken

00:40:35.720 --> 00:40:37.870
up by a startling number of us.

00:40:37.870 --> 00:40:39.510
She's now gone from here,

00:40:39.510 --> 00:40:41.350
and whether she's
enduring her suffering

00:40:41.350 --> 00:40:43.870
or dead is a metaphor
her household,

00:40:43.870 --> 00:40:46.300
whatever their disposition".

00:40:46.300 --> 00:40:47.770
"They're gone too.

00:40:47.770 --> 00:40:50.490
We can talk about her openly

00:40:50.490 --> 00:40:53.500
because hers is no grand
tragedy, no apocalypse

00:40:53.500 --> 00:40:56.760
of the soul or of our times,
yet there are those who would

00:40:56.760 --> 00:41:00.260
like to believe otherwise,
that each and every being

00:41:00.260 --> 00:41:02.870
in the realm is a mock
of micocosum [phonetic]

00:41:02.870 --> 00:41:06.230
of the realm, that we are
hardened and chastened

00:41:06.230 --> 00:41:09.710
and elevated by a
singular reflection.

00:41:09.710 --> 00:41:13.740
This is a fetching idea,
metaphorically and otherwise,

00:41:13.740 --> 00:41:17.850
most often would sit for
promoting the greater good.

00:41:17.850 --> 00:41:19.180
But more and more we can see

00:41:19.180 --> 00:41:24.090
that the question is not
whether we are individuals.

00:41:24.090 --> 00:41:28.570
We can't help but be, this
has been proved case by case.

00:41:28.570 --> 00:41:31.530
We are not drones or
robots and never will be,

00:41:31.530 --> 00:41:34.730
the question then is whether
being an individual makes a

00:41:34.730 --> 00:41:36.070
difference anymore."

00:41:36.070 --> 00:41:39.980
"That it can't matter at
all and if now whether

00:41:39.980 --> 00:41:43.950
in fact we care -- to try
and care about such things.

00:41:43.950 --> 00:41:46.270
Let's suppose another
way of considering here,

00:41:46.270 --> 00:41:51.500
which was that she had a special
conviction of imagination.

00:41:51.500 --> 00:41:54.060
Few of us do to be honest.

00:41:54.060 --> 00:41:56.490
We wish and wish and often
we furiate [phonetic]

00:41:56.490 --> 00:42:01.580
but never very deeply, for if we
did we'd see how the world can

00:42:01.580 --> 00:42:07.690
sometimes be split open
in just the way we hope.

00:42:07.690 --> 00:42:12.510
That it and we, in
fact, are unbounded --

00:42:12.510 --> 00:42:18.870
free" Perhaps it's not obvious
but what I have attempted here

00:42:18.870 --> 00:42:22.630
to do is to weave a personal
history with encounters

00:42:22.630 --> 00:42:27.940
of community, remembered and
imagined as literary registry.

00:42:27.940 --> 00:42:29.240
Why I ended up writing?

00:42:29.240 --> 00:42:31.360
I'm not sure.

00:42:31.360 --> 00:42:34.120
It wasn't genes or
a passionate choice,

00:42:34.120 --> 00:42:38.480
it's probably the only thing
I'm really equipped to do.

00:42:38.480 --> 00:42:41.460
But in reflection of this
journey I have traveled within

00:42:41.460 --> 00:42:43.850
and been a part of
many communities,

00:42:43.850 --> 00:42:46.090
perhaps is the familiar
stranger,

00:42:46.090 --> 00:42:49.260
providentially there
and not there.

00:42:49.260 --> 00:42:54.350
An empathetic observer, wanting
to learn, carry to record --

00:42:54.350 --> 00:42:58.820
that has been my particular
role and contribution.

00:42:58.820 --> 00:43:00.440
There are many writers
whose names

00:43:00.440 --> 00:43:04.170
and words I might have
also shared today.

00:43:04.170 --> 00:43:07.390
But given the time, those
mentioned here are a few

00:43:07.390 --> 00:43:13.310
of those with whom I have
grown up and grown old.

00:43:13.310 --> 00:43:18.150
Immigrants, refugees, exiles
by the fortunes of life,

00:43:18.150 --> 00:43:22.030
have set forth on the
backs of immortal turtles

00:43:22.030 --> 00:43:25.920
to distant places or
perhaps not so distant,

00:43:25.920 --> 00:43:30.520
but alternates display bummed
out realities never again

00:43:30.520 --> 00:43:35.480
to return, or discover that
return is never possible.

00:43:35.480 --> 00:43:38.760
Asian American might
be an imagined island

00:43:38.760 --> 00:43:41.260
or an undersea palace.

00:43:41.260 --> 00:43:45.530
Perhaps it is Hania's
Ibu-bu, Sesshu's East LA

00:43:45.530 --> 00:43:53.700
or Al's I-Hotel, or it is Zach's
limbo, Garrett's somewhere,

00:43:53.700 --> 00:43:56.890
Chang Ray's unbounded world.

00:43:57.990 --> 00:44:03.180
As Yochiko Uchida has retold
the story of Urashima Taro,

00:44:03.180 --> 00:44:07.660
Taro returns from the sea palace
on the back of the gray tortoise

00:44:07.660 --> 00:44:11.640
to his village and finds
it completely changed.

00:44:11.640 --> 00:44:14.260
And where his batch for
home should've been,

00:44:14.260 --> 00:44:18.310
there is an empty lot
full of tall weeds.

00:44:18.310 --> 00:44:21.800
He quirs an old woman,
who he calls a story

00:44:21.800 --> 00:44:24.620
about a young fisherman
named Urashima Taru,

00:44:24.620 --> 00:44:28.800
who went out to fish
and never returned.

00:44:28.800 --> 00:44:33.620
This she uses must have
happened 300 years ago.

00:44:33.620 --> 00:44:38.950
Confused but thinking that
the jewel box gifted to him

00:44:38.950 --> 00:44:45.420
by the princess must hold
an answer, he opens the box.

00:44:45.420 --> 00:44:49.300
Suddenly there rose from
a cloud of white smoke,

00:44:49.300 --> 00:44:53.920
which wrapped itself around
Taro so he could see nothing,

00:44:53.920 --> 00:44:57.390
and when it disappeared,
Urashima Taro appeared

00:44:57.390 --> 00:45:03.250
into the empty box but he
could scarcely hear sea.

00:45:03.250 --> 00:45:06.190
He looked at his hands
and they were the hands

00:45:06.190 --> 00:45:08.700
of an old, old man.

00:45:08.700 --> 00:45:15.210
His face was wrinkled; his
hair was white as snow.

00:45:15.210 --> 00:45:20.290
This year coffee house press
will publish letters to memory,

00:45:20.290 --> 00:45:23.160
and while I'm unable to
characterize the book,

00:45:23.160 --> 00:45:25.820
my editor Carolyn
Casey has said,

00:45:25.820 --> 00:45:29.410
as I say "it is the
word based on an archive

00:45:29.410 --> 00:45:32.560
of family correspondence
documents and photographs,

00:45:32.560 --> 00:45:36.950
the center of which are letters
written between 1938 and 1948,

00:45:36.950 --> 00:45:39.640
capturing the family's
war time dispersal

00:45:39.640 --> 00:45:41.430
from Oakland California,

00:45:41.430 --> 00:45:45.640
to Topaz concentration
camp in Delta, Utah.

00:45:45.640 --> 00:45:49.470
And beyond the schools and work,
in the Midwest and east coast,

00:45:49.470 --> 00:45:50.810
and for a portion of the family,

00:45:50.810 --> 00:45:53.900
their eventual return
to California.

00:45:53.900 --> 00:45:57.560
The form my book has
taken is epistolary --

00:45:57.560 --> 00:46:02.160
that is fictional letters and
what follows is the first part

00:46:02.160 --> 00:46:04.560
of letter until after.

00:46:13.160 --> 00:46:17.710
"Dear Kohele [phonetic],
you're a preacher's kid.

00:46:17.710 --> 00:46:20.340
When we met we recognized
each other immediately

00:46:20.340 --> 00:46:24.810
that pique je ne se
qua, like we're supposed

00:46:24.810 --> 00:46:27.660
to be doing something
significant eventually

00:46:27.660 --> 00:46:30.930
or actually, like we were
raised with everyone looking

00:46:30.930 --> 00:46:34.910
on politely resentful,
assuming we knew --

00:46:34.910 --> 00:46:38.560
when we didn't and thus
perpetual strangers in a world

00:46:38.560 --> 00:46:42.740
of blessed woe, primed
by difference to serve.

00:46:42.740 --> 00:46:45.930
One day I heard your
lecture, and I turned to you

00:46:45.930 --> 00:46:50.210
after in marvel --
'you gave us sermon'.

00:46:50.210 --> 00:46:53.100
You answered 'all my
lectures are sermons'.

00:46:53.100 --> 00:46:55.730
I thought 'mine too, maybe'.

00:46:55.730 --> 00:47:00.950
Frustrate picas, but you must
have really been frustrated

00:47:00.950 --> 00:47:04.040
because finally you entered
the seminary and got a master

00:47:04.040 --> 00:47:05.610
at definity [phonetic].

00:47:05.610 --> 00:47:08.460
I could never do this,
well you believe,

00:47:08.460 --> 00:47:11.080
which is kind of necessary.

00:47:11.080 --> 00:47:14.740
One day I came home from junior
high school and announced

00:47:14.740 --> 00:47:18.630
at dinner that I discovered
a philosopher named John Paul

00:47:18.630 --> 00:47:23.640
Sartre, and a great idea
caught existentialism.

00:47:23.640 --> 00:47:27.190
I can't remember what
my dad John said,

00:47:27.190 --> 00:47:28.650
but that was the beginning.

00:47:28.650 --> 00:47:30.970
I had been that kind of pique.

00:47:30.970 --> 00:47:33.420
Heading out in another
direction where turns

00:47:33.420 --> 00:47:35.350
out anyway to be the same.

00:47:35.350 --> 00:47:36.880
I figured you understand

00:47:36.880 --> 00:47:41.650
and that you'll know the
skinny and funny of it.

00:47:41.650 --> 00:47:45.250
Recently I saw yet another
staging of Shakespeare's

00:47:45.250 --> 00:47:49.570
"King Lear" and I wondered about
those good and bad daughters,

00:47:49.570 --> 00:47:52.610
silent tribute versus
false fanning

00:47:52.610 --> 00:47:55.940
and this reading
of love and honor.

00:47:55.940 --> 00:48:00.130
Do daughters naturally
aspire to be Cordelia?

00:48:00.130 --> 00:48:03.380
Or is this an impossible
and romantic notion

00:48:03.380 --> 00:48:07.760
of set-by-character
and circumstance?

00:48:07.760 --> 00:48:14.130
"No, no, no, no" cries Lear to
Cordelia, broken and unwilling

00:48:14.130 --> 00:48:16.830
to further challenge his fate.

00:48:16.830 --> 00:48:20.560
'Come here' encourages
her 'let's away to prison'

00:48:20.560 --> 00:48:24.730
and then these last
words to his daughter,

00:48:24.730 --> 00:48:31.600
'We too alone will sing
like birds of the cage.

00:48:31.600 --> 00:48:34.190
'When bow does sassy
blessing, I'll kneel down

00:48:34.190 --> 00:48:37.070
and ask of thee forgiveness.

00:48:37.070 --> 00:48:41.260
So, we'll live and pray and sing
and tell old tales and laugh

00:48:41.260 --> 00:48:45.440
at gilded butterflies and hear
poor rogues talk of court news

00:48:45.440 --> 00:48:48.090
and we'll talk with
them too, who loses

00:48:48.090 --> 00:48:50.750
and who wins, who's
in, who's out.

00:48:50.750 --> 00:48:53.650
And take upon us the
mystery of things,

00:48:53.650 --> 00:48:57.390
as if we were God's
spies, and we'll wear

00:48:57.390 --> 00:49:02.310
out in a wall prison packs
and sex on great one that eve

00:49:02.310 --> 00:49:05.140
and flow by the moon'".

00:49:05.140 --> 00:49:13.090
I am drawn to memories in
which we live and pray and sing

00:49:13.090 --> 00:49:16.220
and tell old tales and laugh.

00:49:16.220 --> 00:49:21.760
But this was the laugh, oh but
to laugh at gilded butterflies,

00:49:21.760 --> 00:49:25.630
this must be the satirical
laughter that I am prone to.

00:49:25.630 --> 00:49:29.310
But John would say that
this is not truly laughter,

00:49:29.310 --> 00:49:32.640
not the laughter that
preoccupied his thinking.

00:49:32.640 --> 00:49:36.420
It is not laughter at,
but laughter within,

00:49:36.420 --> 00:49:39.570
I think, that concerned him.

00:49:39.570 --> 00:49:43.500
I am growing old, searching
for this kind of laughter,

00:49:43.500 --> 00:49:48.430
and where is he now that
this laughter is needed most?

00:49:48.430 --> 00:49:53.430
Meanwhile I have found myself
beholden to the lost possibility

00:49:53.430 --> 00:49:56.890
that we take upon us
the mystery of things

00:49:56.890 --> 00:50:00.540
as if we were God's spies.

00:50:00.540 --> 00:50:03.790
Perhaps this has been the
meaning of these letters,

00:50:03.790 --> 00:50:07.490
though surely no
mystery is revealed here.

00:50:07.490 --> 00:50:14.350
Simply we have been
together before time to try.

00:50:16.110 --> 00:50:17.910
Thank you.

00:50:17.910 --> 00:51:03.710
[ Applause ]

