00:55:22.360 --> 00:55:25.030
the provinces where my
Vietnamese refugee parents were

00:55:25.030 --> 00:55:29.000
born and to Dorchester Mass,
where I was born and raised.

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:31.600
I can't believe we're out here
in the library of Congress.

00:55:31.600 --> 00:55:35.640
What a Boston -- all right.

00:55:35.640 --> 00:55:39.740
So, how I generated this piece
-- this is the one-page piece.

00:55:39.740 --> 00:55:41.850
Last year I moved from
New York City to Syracuse

00:55:41.850 --> 00:55:46.410
to begin my MFA program and I
went through a very long breakup

00:55:46.410 --> 00:55:49.270
and had a lot of
trouble finding sleep.

00:55:49.270 --> 00:55:56.100
This piece is called
"2:16a.m.". "On my life,

00:55:56.100 --> 00:55:57.690
I waited to be kept up at night.

00:55:57.690 --> 00:56:00.110
And it finally happened.

00:56:00.110 --> 00:56:03.680
At first, I told myself it'd
been a mistake, but after a week

00:56:03.680 --> 00:56:05.180
of waking up in the
middle of the night,

00:56:05.180 --> 00:56:08.850
I took the red line teleport
to the sleep exchange center

00:56:08.850 --> 00:56:11.130
in the Floating Medical
District.

00:56:11.130 --> 00:56:13.570
I drew a number from
the ticketing machine

00:56:13.570 --> 00:56:16.430
and waited my turn to meet
with a dream official,

00:56:16.430 --> 00:56:18.090
who checked my records.

00:56:18.090 --> 00:56:21.220
Unfortunately, no one
had reported my presence

00:56:21.220 --> 00:56:22.620
in their dream.

00:56:22.620 --> 00:56:25.450
The official assured me that
records were up to date,

00:56:25.450 --> 00:56:28.750
with data gathered each
morning from dream monitors.

00:56:28.750 --> 00:56:30.760
'It might have been that
you were just an extra

00:56:30.760 --> 00:56:33.000
in the background
of someone's dream.

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:36.900
That happens more than you'd
expect' the dream official said.

00:56:36.900 --> 00:56:40.680
'OK' I thought, So, maybe
I wasn't the lead role

00:56:40.680 --> 00:56:45.550
in someone's dream, fine but
my restlessness continued.

00:56:45.550 --> 00:56:48.480
It lasted another
two weeks, then three

00:56:48.480 --> 00:56:53.500
and after a month I resolved to
find out who was keeping me up.

00:56:53.500 --> 00:56:55.390
But how'd I go about it?

00:56:55.390 --> 00:56:59.340
If I asked them politely,
would they stop dreaming?

00:56:59.340 --> 00:57:01.980
Whoever they were,
they've been consistent.

00:57:01.980 --> 00:57:03.700
Maybe they were falling
in love with me,

00:57:03.700 --> 00:57:05.750
if they weren't already.

00:57:05.750 --> 00:57:07.770
In the end, I decided
it would be best

00:57:07.770 --> 00:57:09.680
to wait another week or so.

00:57:09.680 --> 00:57:12.920
For now, the routine
brought me some comfort.

00:57:12.920 --> 00:57:15.760
I fall asleep and
the night wakes me,

00:57:15.760 --> 00:57:18.590
the moon keeps me company
and then I remember

00:57:18.590 --> 00:57:20.190
that when you cannot sleep,

00:57:20.190 --> 00:57:24.790
it is because someone
is dreaming of you."

00:57:24.790 --> 00:57:26.950
All right, oh.

00:57:26.950 --> 00:57:30.790
All right so -- [applause].

00:57:30.790 --> 00:57:36.820
The next story, which is four
pages long, double spaced,

00:57:36.820 --> 00:57:40.050
is called "Tiger, Tiger".

00:57:41.770 --> 00:57:47.200
"The portal dropped the child
an unfamiliar ground" --

00:57:47.200 --> 00:57:48.760
that's right, there's a portal.

00:57:48.760 --> 00:57:52.800
"Against all decrees of
high science and witchcraft,

00:57:52.800 --> 00:57:55.190
her uncle had summoned it.

00:57:55.190 --> 00:57:57.590
Our world is finished', he said,

00:57:57.590 --> 00:58:01.140
'you and what I had trust you
now will be the last reminisce

00:58:01.140 --> 00:58:03.510
of our civilization'.

00:58:03.510 --> 00:58:04.940
He opened the child's rug sack

00:58:04.940 --> 00:58:07.920
and placed inside
it a large parcel.

00:58:07.920 --> 00:58:10.520
'Do with it what you wish'.

00:58:10.520 --> 00:58:12.420
The child adjusted the
straps on his shoulders

00:58:12.420 --> 00:58:14.610
to settle the weight
on her back.

00:58:14.610 --> 00:58:17.170
Outside the three-night
moons were falling

00:58:17.170 --> 00:58:19.600
from the sky toward her planet.

00:58:19.600 --> 00:58:23.090
If she felt distressed,
her face betrayed nothing.

00:58:23.090 --> 00:58:26.190
But her uncle sensed it, and
in these final moments he broke

00:58:26.190 --> 00:58:30.360
with social procedures
and attempted sympathy.

00:58:30.360 --> 00:58:33.960
'While this is certainly not the
time to disorient my faculties

00:58:33.960 --> 00:58:38.540
with sentimentality' -- he said
-- then he paused 'my niece,

00:58:38.540 --> 00:58:41.610
what I mean to say is
if we should meet again

00:58:41.610 --> 00:58:46.060
in the next life, I hope'
-- before he could finish,

00:58:46.060 --> 00:58:49.420
the white maids rode through the
gates and an explosion of smoke

00:58:49.420 --> 00:58:52.370
and lighting had struck
her uncle down dead.

00:58:52.370 --> 00:58:57.250
The force of the blow knocked
the child through the portal.

00:58:57.250 --> 00:58:59.520
The sound of rushing
water will care.

00:58:59.520 --> 00:59:01.000
She was in a clotted
forest surrounded

00:59:01.000 --> 00:59:03.420
by tall towers of limestone.

00:59:03.420 --> 00:59:06.160
She'd lost track of her rug
sack and searched for it,

00:59:06.160 --> 00:59:08.630
before locating it
by the riverbank.

00:59:08.630 --> 00:59:12.930
Streams lumps had formed inside
it and were shifting around,

00:59:12.930 --> 00:59:17.380
slowly, like an owl snake
uncoiling its feathers,

00:59:17.380 --> 00:59:19.630
the top of the rug
sack flew open

00:59:19.630 --> 00:59:23.610
and out tumbled two tiger cubs.

00:59:23.610 --> 00:59:25.990
The child was struck
by how small they were,

00:59:25.990 --> 00:59:29.100
how they lacked mastery
over their motor skills.

00:59:29.100 --> 00:59:31.650
But the most extraordinary
characteristic

00:59:31.650 --> 00:59:35.550
about them was they
emitted not a single sound.

00:59:35.550 --> 00:59:40.960
Not a meow, squeak nor purr
-- they were silent tigers.

00:59:40.960 --> 00:59:44.900
After they shared a deep
drink from the river,

00:59:44.900 --> 00:59:46.200
the child scoot them up

00:59:46.200 --> 00:59:49.130
and secured them back
inside her rug sack.

00:59:49.130 --> 00:59:52.660
She found a road and
road it for many days.

00:59:52.660 --> 00:59:55.330
The tiger cubs were so
quiet, if it hadn't been

00:59:55.330 --> 00:59:57.460
for their intermittent
wrestling matches,

00:59:57.460 --> 01:00:00.090
she would've assumed
they expired.

01:00:00.090 --> 01:00:03.160
By the time she reached the
port town the tiger cubs were

01:00:03.160 --> 01:00:06.090
perpetually falling asleep.

01:00:06.090 --> 01:00:09.150
Every so often, she reached
behind her to scratch their ears

01:00:09.150 --> 01:00:13.350
and pet their bellies to
ensure they could still wake.

01:00:13.350 --> 01:00:14.880
They did not find the rest

01:00:14.880 --> 01:00:17.450
that they'd hoped
for in the port town.

01:00:17.450 --> 01:00:20.570
The citizens demanded payment
before they would provide the

01:00:20.570 --> 01:00:23.650
child with food and shelter.

01:00:23.650 --> 01:00:27.010
"Unfortunately, I have nothing",
she said, standing up straighter

01:00:27.010 --> 01:00:30.660
to keep her rucksack and
tiger cubs out of sight.

01:00:30.660 --> 01:00:33.650
Her stomach contracted with
hunger, and she felt the paws

01:00:33.650 --> 01:00:36.570
of the tiger cubs
kneading her back.

01:00:36.570 --> 01:00:41.120
She thought of her uncle's last
words, the world they lost,

01:00:41.120 --> 01:00:44.330
the difficult choice
she now had to make.

01:00:44.330 --> 01:00:47.740
She found the section of the
market where animals were sold,

01:00:47.740 --> 01:00:51.480
and lifted the two tiger
cubs out of her rucksack.

01:00:51.480 --> 01:00:53.680
Many collectors inquired
about them,

01:00:53.680 --> 01:00:57.090
but when the tigers' vocal
derangement was revealed,

01:00:57.090 --> 01:00:58.700
customers left.

01:00:58.700 --> 01:01:01.180
"Of what use are mute
tigers?", They said.

01:01:01.180 --> 01:01:05.700
The merchants were closing down
the market stalls for the night

01:01:05.700 --> 01:01:09.680
when a gust of wind blew through
the town, a woman shrouded

01:01:09.680 --> 01:01:12.730
in a tattered cloak limped
slowly toward the child

01:01:12.730 --> 01:01:15.020
and her silent tiger cubs.

01:01:15.020 --> 01:01:17.190
In exchange for one
of the tigers,

01:01:17.190 --> 01:01:19.850
she presented the
child with a machete.

01:01:19.850 --> 01:01:24.030
"It is enchanted", the cloaked
figure said before slipping away

01:01:24.030 --> 01:01:26.510
into memory.

01:01:26.510 --> 01:01:29.210
The child and the
remaining tiger continued

01:01:29.210 --> 01:01:31.270
on in this new world.

01:01:31.270 --> 01:01:33.210
When the child wielded
it, she could cut

01:01:33.210 --> 01:01:36.870
through the thickest tree truck,
the densest seal, but they kept

01:01:36.870 --> 01:01:39.160
to themselves and
focused on the mundane

01:01:39.160 --> 01:01:41.590
but peaceful task of living.

01:01:41.590 --> 01:01:44.390
The child collected firewood
while the tiger watched her

01:01:44.390 --> 01:01:45.690
from a tree.

01:01:45.690 --> 01:01:48.850
The tiger a into lakes
and rivers to catch fish,

01:01:48.850 --> 01:01:51.400
and the child cleaned
it with her machete.

01:01:51.400 --> 01:01:54.250
They raced across the forest
together, the child clinging

01:01:54.250 --> 01:01:56.700
to the back of the tiger.

01:01:56.700 --> 01:02:01.430
They played the way cats would,
pouncing, racing, fighting.

01:02:01.430 --> 01:02:03.520
They moved on when restless.

01:02:03.520 --> 01:02:06.800
They slept out on open fields
and watched shooting stars,

01:02:06.800 --> 01:02:09.370
tracing it with their
fingers and claws

01:02:09.370 --> 01:02:12.760
like they were the ones
tearing up the sky.

01:02:12.760 --> 01:02:15.790
Sometimes they wondered about
the lost member of their trio,

01:02:15.790 --> 01:02:19.010
but never discussed it in the
language that they shared.

01:02:19.010 --> 01:02:20.890
"Dwelling in the
past is not essential

01:02:20.890 --> 01:02:25.110
for surviving the present",
she could hear her uncle say.

01:02:25.110 --> 01:02:29.000
The child grew into a woman,
the cub into an adult tiger,

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:32.750
but still they were hunted
by a lingering sense of loss.

01:02:32.750 --> 01:02:34.690
Consequently, they
never wandered too far

01:02:34.690 --> 01:02:36.070
from each other.

01:02:36.070 --> 01:02:37.870
Like the sun and the
moon, when one appeared,

01:02:37.870 --> 01:02:40.700
the other was not far behind.

01:02:40.700 --> 01:02:43.140
When they reached the city
between two mountains,

01:02:43.140 --> 01:02:46.720
an assembly of witches
and warriors approached.

01:02:46.720 --> 01:02:50.050
A white mage was wreaking havoc
at the edge of their world

01:02:50.050 --> 01:02:52.080
and they were going to stop him.

01:02:52.080 --> 01:02:56.320
Would the young woman warrior
and her battle tiger join them?

01:02:56.320 --> 01:03:00.110
The two conferred privately
before arriving at a decision.

01:03:00.110 --> 01:03:02.750
"Certainly!", the child
said to the assembly,

01:03:02.750 --> 01:03:05.090
"Our own home world is lost.

01:03:05.090 --> 01:03:07.880
We have grown accustomed to
this one and would prefer

01:03:07.880 --> 01:03:09.910
that it not end prematurely".

01:03:09.910 --> 01:03:13.640
The child and her tiger covered
many lands with the assembly

01:03:13.640 --> 01:03:15.970
of witches and warriors
and fought hard

01:03:15.970 --> 01:03:19.660
against the sorcerers and goblin
soldiers of the white mage.

01:03:19.660 --> 01:03:22.640
They rushed headlong into war,
clearing entire battalions

01:03:22.640 --> 01:03:24.850
with their combined ferocity.

01:03:24.850 --> 01:03:27.630
The tiger's sharp claws
and fearsome teeth,

01:03:27.630 --> 01:03:31.050
the child's strength and skill
with her enchanted machete,

01:03:31.050 --> 01:03:34.400
these helped to turn the
tide of crucial battles.

01:03:34.400 --> 01:03:37.340
In the final confrontation,
however, the warriors

01:03:37.340 --> 01:03:40.520
and witches were
thoroughly laid to waste,

01:03:40.520 --> 01:03:43.170
their contorted corpses
were scattered at the feet

01:03:43.170 --> 01:03:45.900
of the white mage
in his throne room.

01:03:45.900 --> 01:03:48.870
-- I have destroyed countless
worlds, and will continue doing

01:03:48.870 --> 01:03:53.410
so -- he said -- Who are
you to suggest otherwise?

01:03:53.410 --> 01:03:55.360
-- The child braced
her enchanted machete

01:03:55.360 --> 01:03:57.390
and struggled to her feet.

01:03:57.390 --> 01:03:58.950
Suddenly, she felt a touch

01:03:58.950 --> 01:04:02.480
on her shoulder beckoning
her to stay down.

01:04:02.480 --> 01:04:06.130
It was her tiger, whose fur
was covered in deep gashes

01:04:06.130 --> 01:04:08.990
and purple patches of blood.

01:04:08.990 --> 01:04:12.400
-- The silent tiger from a
lost world -- said the mage --

01:04:12.400 --> 01:04:15.920
How utterly useless -- The
tiger lurched from the center

01:04:15.920 --> 01:04:19.020
of the throne room to
face the white mage.

01:04:19.020 --> 01:04:20.900
Then, it crouched
close to the ground,

01:04:20.900 --> 01:04:23.370
and exploded into a sprint.

01:04:23.370 --> 01:04:25.250
Just as it was about to pounce,

01:04:25.250 --> 01:04:27.350
the white mage conjured
a frost spell,

01:04:27.350 --> 01:04:29.820
and hurled a shard
of ice at the child.

01:04:29.820 --> 01:04:33.300
In an instant the tiger
changed course midair

01:04:33.300 --> 01:04:35.950
and leapt out in front of it.

01:04:35.950 --> 01:04:38.230
The ice tore into the
tiger's soft belly

01:04:38.230 --> 01:04:41.490
and remained there
until it melted.

01:04:41.490 --> 01:04:44.570
The child dragged herself over
to her tiger and turned her back

01:04:44.570 --> 01:04:47.930
to the white mage to shield
her wounded companion.

01:04:47.930 --> 01:04:52.010
She alternated between
scolding and thanking the tiger.

01:04:52.010 --> 01:04:54.840
Sensing this was the end,
she cried for her world,

01:04:54.840 --> 01:04:57.460
her uncle, and her tow tigers.

01:04:57.460 --> 01:05:01.220
She scratched behind the tiger's
ears and stroked its tail.

01:05:01.220 --> 01:05:04.400
The tiger nuzzled
her calloused hands.

01:05:04.400 --> 01:05:07.100
-- Please, forgive me for
separating you from your sibling

01:05:07.100 --> 01:05:09.470
when you were merely
cubs -- she said --

01:05:09.470 --> 01:05:13.140
I was immature and lacked the
requisite sources, material

01:05:13.140 --> 01:05:16.820
and intellectual, to
keep your bond intact --

01:05:16.820 --> 01:05:18.960
Looking at her, the tiger purred

01:05:18.960 --> 01:05:22.840
until the ground
trembled, and then died.

01:05:22.840 --> 01:05:24.780
In rage, she picked up
her enchanted machete

01:05:24.780 --> 01:05:26.770
and hurled it at the white mage.

01:05:26.770 --> 01:05:28.580
It pierced through
his magic defenses

01:05:28.580 --> 01:05:30.860
and struck him in the chest.

01:05:30.860 --> 01:05:32.610
The white mage burst
into flames,

01:05:32.610 --> 01:05:34.830
and his magical powers
dispersed,

01:05:34.830 --> 01:05:37.470
ripping open another portal.

01:05:37.470 --> 01:05:41.180
A voice called from beyond,
"Hold a time and place

01:05:41.180 --> 01:05:44.280
in your mind, and step through".

01:05:44.280 --> 01:05:46.880
The child picked up
her enchanted machete,

01:05:46.880 --> 01:05:49.670
and stepped toward the portal.

01:05:49.670 --> 01:05:52.560
-- The white mage is dead, and
my tiger has deserted me --

01:05:52.560 --> 01:05:56.200
she said -- Never did I
envision standing once again

01:05:56.200 --> 01:05:58.530
on the crimson shores
of my home planet

01:05:58.530 --> 01:06:01.520
to gaze upon the
three-night moons".

01:06:01.520 --> 01:06:04.310
Machete in hand, a
time and place held

01:06:04.310 --> 01:06:07.680
in her mind, she
stepped through.

01:06:10.150 --> 01:06:14.270
The portal deposited
her in a port town.

01:06:14.270 --> 01:06:16.330
She found a tattered
cloth in the ground

01:06:16.330 --> 01:06:18.790
and wrapped it around
her shoulders.

01:06:18.790 --> 01:06:21.260
She remembered where
she needed to go.

01:06:21.260 --> 01:06:23.750
The merchants were closing down
the market stalls for the night,

01:06:23.750 --> 01:06:26.470
and in the section where
animals are being sold,

01:06:26.470 --> 01:06:29.490
a child stood holding
out a rucksack.

01:06:29.490 --> 01:06:33.260
She limped slowly toward the
child and traded her machete

01:06:33.260 --> 01:06:36.660
for one of the two
silent tiger cubs.

01:06:36.660 --> 01:06:39.790
-- It is enchanted -- she
said before slipping away

01:06:39.790 --> 01:06:41.810
into memory.

01:06:41.810 --> 01:06:43.610
Thank you.

01:06:43.610 --> 01:06:55.200
[ Applause ]

01:06:55.200 --> 01:06:58.930
&gt;&gt; Lisa Sasaki: All I have to
say is Vt does have a kitty,

01:06:58.930 --> 01:07:02.450
and I just imagined that he
wrote that just like tumbling

01:07:02.450 --> 01:07:04.240
around with your kitty,
and that's very cute

01:07:04.240 --> 01:07:06.170
so thank you for that.

01:07:06.170 --> 01:07:09.150
Our next reader is Mark Keats.

01:07:09.150 --> 01:07:12.900
Mark Keats was adopted from
South Korea at the age of three.

01:07:12.900 --> 01:07:15.420
He earned his MFA in Fiction
at the University of Maryland

01:07:15.420 --> 01:07:18.200
and is a recipient of
a Kundiman Fellowship.

01:07:18.200 --> 01:07:21.180
His work has appeared or is
forthcoming in [inaudible]

01:07:21.180 --> 01:07:24.380
with Ron Corderly
[phonetic] and others,

01:07:24.380 --> 01:07:28.320
and he's currently a PhD
candidate in the English

01:07:28.320 --> 01:07:31.870
and Creative Writing Program
at Texas Tech University.

01:07:31.870 --> 01:07:34.780
I know he's currently
dissertating.

01:07:34.780 --> 01:07:39.340
So, please give Mark
a warm welcome

01:07:39.340 --> 01:07:41.510
in the middle of
his dissertation!

01:07:41.510 --> 01:07:50.600
[ Applause ]

01:07:50.600 --> 01:07:58.140
&gt;&gt; Mark Yeats: This is not
intimidating at all, right?

01:07:58.140 --> 01:08:00.750
[laughter] I would also like
to thank Karen Tei Yamashita

01:08:00.750 --> 01:08:05.120
for her lovely lecture, I
think it's very appropriate.

01:08:05.120 --> 01:08:07.890
It's very shocking to
me, a literary hero

01:08:07.890 --> 01:08:10.490
and also someone whose books
are on my reading list,

01:08:10.490 --> 01:08:14.560
it's sort of very interesting
to sort of accepting

01:08:14.560 --> 01:08:16.880
that continuity of Asian
American literature,

01:08:16.880 --> 01:08:18.790
to be part of that.

01:08:18.790 --> 01:08:21.620
I would like to thank
the Smithsonian,

01:08:21.620 --> 01:08:24.430
the Library of Congress, the
Asian American Literary Review,

01:08:24.430 --> 01:08:27.000
and especially Kundiman.

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:28.790
I had not heard of Kundiman.

01:08:28.790 --> 01:08:33.890
I still don't know quite perhaps
who first told me about them,

01:08:33.890 --> 01:08:36.720
but [inaudible] if it was
worth, you know, applying again

01:08:36.720 --> 01:08:40.060
because I was not part of
the first fiction concord,

01:08:40.060 --> 01:08:42.110
and he said resoundingly
"Yes, apply.

01:08:42.110 --> 01:08:44.520
It will change your
life" And so, I did,

01:08:44.520 --> 01:08:46.370
and I participated last year,

01:08:46.370 --> 01:08:48.620
and it certainly
did change my life.

01:08:48.620 --> 01:08:52.030
I think the first thing it
did ultimately was to suggest

01:08:52.030 --> 01:08:54.500
that there's this community of
other Asian American writers

01:08:54.500 --> 01:08:58.050
out there that are
struggling and succeeding,

01:08:58.050 --> 01:09:00.990
and pursuing writing, not just
sort of as a side project,

01:09:00.990 --> 01:09:03.960
but for their career, and I
was just overwhelmed by that.

01:09:03.960 --> 01:09:06.760
I would also say that I've never
felt that comfortable in a group

01:09:06.760 --> 01:09:09.950
of people, and so it's
a lovely experience

01:09:09.950 --> 01:09:12.250
to fell just sort of yourself.

01:09:12.250 --> 01:09:16.210
I'm going to read
three short pieces.

01:09:16.210 --> 01:09:20.990
The first piece is called
"Adoptive Fragment number five".

01:09:20.990 --> 01:09:23.760
When you ask, they will
say, "Your birthmother,

01:09:23.760 --> 01:09:25.460
she made a tough decision".

01:09:25.460 --> 01:09:28.100
You'll think, "But she decided".

01:09:28.100 --> 01:09:30.770
When you ask your adoptive
mother, she will say,

01:09:30.770 --> 01:09:32.070
"I've always loved you.

01:09:32.070 --> 01:09:33.370
I've always known".

01:09:33.370 --> 01:09:36.510
She will kneel down and put her
arms around you, and look you

01:09:36.510 --> 01:09:38.670
in the eyes, "I choose you".

01:09:38.670 --> 01:09:40.960
You will think, "You decided"

01:09:40.960 --> 01:09:42.330
When you ask your
adoptive father,

01:09:42.330 --> 01:09:43.710
he will not speak right away.

01:09:43.710 --> 01:09:45.160
It has never been his way.

01:09:45.160 --> 01:09:49.560
Instead, he will hold his coffee
mug midair, purse his lips,

01:09:49.560 --> 01:09:51.340
consider his response.

01:09:51.340 --> 01:09:55.260
He will say, "Well, of course,
what your mother said is true.

01:09:55.260 --> 01:09:57.130
We saw your picture and knew".

01:09:57.130 --> 01:10:00.040
You will think, "Yes, of course"

01:10:00.040 --> 01:10:01.880
"You knew, and you decided".

01:10:01.880 --> 01:10:04.540
When you ask your adoptive
older brother, he will shrug,

01:10:04.540 --> 01:10:07.480
smile uneasily, say,
"What's it matter?

01:10:07.480 --> 01:10:09.080
You're my sister.

01:10:09.080 --> 01:10:11.760
"Yes", you will think,
"It was decided".

01:10:11.760 --> 01:10:14.730
When you ask your dog, she
will look at you calmly,

01:10:14.730 --> 01:10:18.190
her tail thumping lightly,
she will bark once and again,

01:10:18.190 --> 01:10:21.380
and you will know somehow that
the translation will be that,

01:10:21.380 --> 01:10:23.460
"it has always been decided".

01:10:23.460 --> 01:10:28.330
This next piece, and I do
want to give a shoot at,

01:10:28.330 --> 01:10:30.440
this piece was published in
[inaudible] and they're based

01:10:30.440 --> 01:10:34.060
out in Burke, Virginia,
which is pretty local here,

01:10:34.060 --> 01:10:35.540
and to their editor
Cara Lakowski [phonetic]

01:10:35.540 --> 01:10:38.160
who was a big part
of this story,

01:10:38.160 --> 01:10:40.100
and when they published
this, it really made me feel

01:10:40.100 --> 01:10:41.400
like a writer finally, right?

01:10:41.400 --> 01:10:42.700
When you publish something --

01:10:42.700 --> 01:10:47.060
"Lessons from Oregon"
The [inaudible] is rain.

01:10:47.060 --> 01:10:48.660
I don't have to tell
you about that, right?

01:10:48.660 --> 01:10:51.830
It doesn't reveal itself
until after October.

01:10:51.830 --> 01:10:54.840
Then, it rains a lot,
but during September,

01:10:54.840 --> 01:10:57.200
the month I was supposedly
born, the weatherman said

01:10:57.200 --> 01:10:59.870
that it would be
gray and menacing,

01:10:59.870 --> 01:11:02.490
the rain wouldn't happen
until Thursday this week.

01:11:02.490 --> 01:11:04.470
And I had trusted
him, his voice,

01:11:04.470 --> 01:11:07.370
his way of predicting
[inaudible].

01:11:07.370 --> 01:11:09.850
As I walked to work on
Tuesday, wondering how I came

01:11:09.850 --> 01:11:12.170
to be teaching elementary
school children about parts

01:11:12.170 --> 01:11:14.130
of speech, it rained hard.

01:11:14.130 --> 01:11:16.440
Then, as if it wanted
to surprise me,

01:11:16.440 --> 01:11:19.400
show its capriciousness, stopped
once I reached the school's

01:11:19.400 --> 01:11:20.860
large glass door.

01:11:20.860 --> 01:11:22.720
Hair matted down
form the wetness,

01:11:22.720 --> 01:11:25.500
another teacher opened the
door, looked and said to me --

01:11:25.500 --> 01:11:27.410
Where's your umbrella?

01:11:27.410 --> 01:11:30.070
-- The man said it wouldn't
rain until Thursday --

01:11:30.070 --> 01:11:33.670
She responded -- Silly boy,
always bring your umbrella --

01:11:33.670 --> 01:11:37.990
Lesson one -- always bring your
umbrella [inaudible] Assumption

01:11:37.990 --> 01:11:42.150
-- you have an umbrella
[inaudible] Coffee is clearly

01:11:42.150 --> 01:11:43.450
better here, I think.

01:11:43.450 --> 01:11:45.930
It doesn't matter when
I drink coffee anymore.

01:11:45.930 --> 01:11:47.760
Sometimes after I
drink, I fall asleep,

01:11:47.760 --> 01:11:50.090
as if I drank to fall asleep.

01:11:50.090 --> 01:11:52.670
And when I dream, I
dream I have three cats,

01:11:52.670 --> 01:11:54.540
three brand new cats.

01:11:54.540 --> 01:11:56.110
I've always been a dog person,

01:11:56.110 --> 01:11:58.870
so I don't know what the
dream means [laughter].

01:11:58.870 --> 01:12:00.870
It bothers me that I'd have
so many cats [laughter].

01:12:00.870 --> 01:12:05.010
But now after a few
months, I can't sleep.

01:12:05.010 --> 01:12:07.570
So, I drink more and
think of those three cats,

01:12:07.570 --> 01:12:10.460
their names, their
personalities.

01:12:10.460 --> 01:12:11.950
I run on the apartment's
treadmills at two

01:12:11.950 --> 01:12:15.310
in the morning, and come up
with names like Larry, Louis,

01:12:15.310 --> 01:12:19.040
Leopold, all names that might
reflect where I was raised.

01:12:19.040 --> 01:12:20.340
Lesson two -- adjusting

01:12:20.340 --> 01:12:22.840
to the time difference will
take longer than expected.

01:12:22.840 --> 01:12:24.980
Lesson 2.5 -- get a cat,

01:12:24.980 --> 01:12:29.010
maybe two because the
apartment doesn't allow dogs.

01:12:29.010 --> 01:12:30.790
-- Sure -- I say to my
mother, who happened to forget

01:12:30.790 --> 01:12:32.760
about the three-hour
time difference,

01:12:32.760 --> 01:12:34.810
but I'm awake -- the insomnia.

01:12:34.810 --> 01:12:36.860
I boil water to run
the French press.

01:12:36.860 --> 01:12:39.480
Does it really make a
difference if it's 3:30am here,

01:12:39.480 --> 01:12:43.000
6:30am on the East Coast,
when your mother calls?

01:12:43.000 --> 01:12:44.300
-- How's my favorite son doing?

01:12:44.300 --> 01:12:46.890
-- She asks -- I'm your
only son -- I say --

01:12:46.890 --> 01:12:48.340
You didn't answer
the question --

01:12:48.340 --> 01:12:50.930
she says [laughter]
Lesson three --

01:12:50.930 --> 01:12:53.500
you can't hide from your mother,

01:12:53.500 --> 01:12:56.490
even on the West
Coast [laughter].

01:12:56.490 --> 01:13:00.350
mom calls again early -- Did
you check the top cabinet?

01:13:00.350 --> 01:13:01.650
-- I say, looking out my window.

01:13:01.650 --> 01:13:05.190
I hear the cabinet door
ease open, then close shut.

01:13:05.190 --> 01:13:06.560
-- Thank you -- she says --

01:13:06.560 --> 01:13:08.570
I don't know what
I'd do without you --

01:13:08.570 --> 01:13:11.390
You seem to be doing OK -- I
say -- did you make a decision?

01:13:11.390 --> 01:13:13.710
-- She says -- are
you going to meet her?

01:13:13.710 --> 01:13:16.000
Oh, I almost forgot -- she
adds -- your cousin Laura,

01:13:16.000 --> 01:13:18.550
she's pregnant -- Lesson four --

01:13:18.550 --> 01:13:21.210
be born or adopted into
a family with siblings.

01:13:21.210 --> 01:13:23.950
Lesson 4.5 -- get mom a hobby,

01:13:23.950 --> 01:13:28.570
maybe a cat [laughter] Lesson
4.75 -- when you're adopted,

01:13:28.570 --> 01:13:30.050
birthmothers will
find you [laughter].

01:13:30.050 --> 01:13:32.460
The school where
I teach English,

01:13:32.460 --> 01:13:34.680
Fiona asked me why I talk funny.

01:13:34.680 --> 01:13:36.860
She has a large mole
near her bottom lip,

01:13:36.860 --> 01:13:39.310
with her hair pulled back
in pigtails, and the kind

01:13:39.310 --> 01:13:40.730
of earnest expression synonymous

01:13:40.730 --> 01:13:42.720
with first graders
and their questions.

01:13:42.720 --> 01:13:45.270
-- Funny? -- I repeat,
looking at her,

01:13:45.270 --> 01:13:47.710
unsure if I can really
hear what she hears.

01:13:47.710 --> 01:13:50.780
-- Fiona -- I say, about to
talk about regional dialects,

01:13:50.780 --> 01:13:52.370
before I realize I don't
know how to explain

01:13:52.370 --> 01:13:54.290
that to a first grader.

01:13:54.290 --> 01:13:58.270
Lesson five -- stop talking
funny [laughter] Also,

01:13:58.270 --> 01:13:59.640
no more stickers for
Fiona [laughter].

01:13:59.640 --> 01:14:00.940
It's fiction.

01:14:00.940 --> 01:14:02.240
It's OK, right?

01:14:02.240 --> 01:14:03.540
[Laughter].

01:14:03.540 --> 01:14:09.220
I named my cats Louis
and Clark; the irony is

01:14:09.220 --> 01:14:11.550
that they're indoor cats and
I live in a studio [laughter].

01:14:11.550 --> 01:14:14.380
When they follow me around,

01:14:14.380 --> 01:14:16.180
I pretend that I'm
the Columbia River,

01:14:16.180 --> 01:14:19.100
so I sneak around the
apartment with them in toe.

01:14:19.100 --> 01:14:20.680
Sometimes I create
an obstacle for them

01:14:20.680 --> 01:14:22.180
and say, "This won't easy.

01:14:22.180 --> 01:14:25.530
[Inaudible] and marking
new lands is never easy",

01:14:25.530 --> 01:14:27.750
but they just rub
against my leg,

01:14:27.750 --> 01:14:29.790
wait for me to bend
down and pet them.

01:14:29.790 --> 01:14:33.420
Lesson 6 -- get a hobby
and/or get out more.

01:14:33.420 --> 01:14:37.470
A cannon beach on an unclear day
[inaudible] my house reminds me

01:14:37.470 --> 01:14:40.660
of one of my favorite painting
"Wanderer above the Sea of Fog".

01:14:40.660 --> 01:14:43.230
It's been six month since I was
laid off and move to the west

01:14:43.230 --> 01:14:46.380
from the East Coast, away
from family and friends,

01:14:46.380 --> 01:14:49.380
away from familiarity,
away from the letter

01:14:49.380 --> 01:14:52.250
that had arrived telling me
that she was looking for me,

01:14:52.250 --> 01:14:55.040
and I think as my shoes make
sets of impressions on the firm

01:14:55.040 --> 01:14:58.270
and sooty-looking sand, as
the strong wind fills my shoes

01:14:58.270 --> 01:15:01.090
with imperceptible pieces,
"I think all we needed was

01:15:01.090 --> 01:15:02.660
to keep pretending
that we didn't exist,

01:15:02.660 --> 01:15:05.510
that we didn't need each
other, that it was OK,

01:15:05.510 --> 01:15:09.840
that we forgave each other, that
that sometimes happens in life".

01:15:09.840 --> 01:15:12.580
But when that letter
came, the distance

01:15:12.580 --> 01:15:15.990
that the [inaudible] became a
momentary lapse, merely a delay

01:15:15.990 --> 01:15:18.320
between the things we had
meant to say, the things some

01:15:18.320 --> 01:15:21.530
of us hoped to say, and I hear
it in my head when I imagine

01:15:21.530 --> 01:15:23.590
and hope that she
will say, "I'm sorry,

01:15:23.590 --> 01:15:27.040
I'm sorry" Lesson seven -- there
are unforeseen consequences

01:15:27.040 --> 01:15:28.410
to everyone's actions.

01:15:28.410 --> 01:15:34.000
In this last piece -- actually,
I wrote it for my wife,

01:15:34.000 --> 01:15:36.770
who is in the audience
struggling to have some sleep,

01:15:36.770 --> 01:15:39.490
she worked a night shift
as an ICU nurse last night,

01:15:39.490 --> 01:15:42.120
so I'm grateful that she's here.

01:15:42.120 --> 01:15:45.130
It's real brief, it's
called "Family Traits".

01:15:45.130 --> 01:15:48.440
It's an elusive thing,
one I assume we will see

01:15:48.440 --> 01:15:51.590
when the baby comes,
if the baby comes.

01:15:51.590 --> 01:15:54.700
So much depends on the baby,
I think, for us to see.

01:15:54.700 --> 01:15:57.660
In my friends' family photos,
it's almost always the eyes,

01:15:57.660 --> 01:16:00.940
and sometimes it's the
nose, the cheekbones,

01:16:00.940 --> 01:16:03.730
the way they all smile,
sometimes serious, sometimes,

01:16:03.730 --> 01:16:07.230
not so much, perhaps,
even caught in the moment.

01:16:07.230 --> 01:16:08.530
You can't hide that, I think,

01:16:08.530 --> 01:16:10.940
no matter how much my friend
tells me she'll never be

01:16:10.940 --> 01:16:13.250
like her mother or father.

01:16:13.250 --> 01:16:16.120
Even in my family I can see
it, though it's less genetic.

01:16:16.120 --> 01:16:18.600
The way we sometimes slide
our hands through our hair,

01:16:18.600 --> 01:16:21.090
raise our eyebrows
a little, exhale.

01:16:21.090 --> 01:16:22.590
It's in the way we eat,
and though I don't go

01:16:22.590 --> 01:16:24.960
to church anymore, the
way I fold my hands

01:16:24.960 --> 01:16:26.560
and bow my head a little.

01:16:26.560 --> 01:16:29.160
It's in the constant worrying
and unnecessary apologizing

01:16:29.160 --> 01:16:30.910
for the simplest thing.

01:16:30.910 --> 01:16:32.740
The dog, too, has
gotten in on the act,

01:16:32.740 --> 01:16:35.150
as if he's forgotten
his previous doggy life

01:16:35.150 --> 01:16:39.170
in West Texas and absorbed
[inaudible] East Coast.

01:16:39.170 --> 01:16:42.160
Sometimes, when he sits by the
slider and peers out, it's hard,

01:16:42.160 --> 01:16:44.930
you say, not to think about
me in the other room reading,

01:16:44.930 --> 01:16:46.230
looking at a window,

01:16:46.230 --> 01:16:48.070
and wondering also
what they look like,

01:16:48.070 --> 01:16:49.370
what they both look like.

01:16:49.370 --> 01:16:51.160
And, of course, I
find myself thinking

01:16:51.160 --> 01:16:54.250
about your parents too back
in Korea, and the face I fell

01:16:54.250 --> 01:16:57.060
in love with might be
separated into two.

01:16:57.060 --> 01:16:58.860
Thank you very much.

01:16:58.860 --> 01:17:09.050
[ Applause ]

01:17:09.050 --> 01:17:10.610
&gt;&gt; Lisa Sasaki: That's so great.

01:17:10.610 --> 01:17:11.950
Thank you, Mark.

01:17:11.950 --> 01:17:15.830
Actually, I just wanted to
just mention that Kundiman,

01:17:15.830 --> 01:17:20.530
we have for 14 years
sponsored a retreat.

01:17:20.530 --> 01:17:25.630
So, that's how everybody
knows each other.

01:17:25.630 --> 01:17:33.150
It is at Fordham University
in the Bronx, and people apply

01:17:33.150 --> 01:17:40.500
and 18 writers per genre,
poetry and prose come together,

01:17:40.500 --> 01:17:48.080
and study with like six
total, but three writer

01:17:48.080 --> 01:17:49.840
who are a bit more established.

01:17:49.840 --> 01:17:56.000
So, it is a community but we
also are very much looking to --

01:17:56.000 --> 01:18:03.590
programs like these help enable
us to reach a wider audience

01:18:03.590 --> 01:18:05.960
and to welcome more people in.

01:18:05.960 --> 01:18:08.500
It's an intimate program,
but we want to continue

01:18:08.500 --> 01:18:11.290
to welcome people into
the cult, so thank you.

01:18:11.290 --> 01:18:15.230
OK, our last and
final reader, our last

01:18:15.230 --> 01:18:18.590
and final last [laughter]
I'm a writer too, apparently.

01:18:18.590 --> 01:18:21.810
Our last reader is Sejal Shah.

01:18:21.810 --> 01:18:23.170
Sejal's essays have appeared

01:18:23.170 --> 01:18:25.880
in the Asian American
Literary Review, Brevity,

01:18:25.880 --> 01:18:28.010
The Kenian Review
online, Waxwing,

01:18:28.010 --> 01:18:30.610
and several anthologies,
including the just released

01:18:30.610 --> 01:18:33.380
"Mad Heart, Be Brave:
Essays on the Poetry

01:18:33.380 --> 01:18:37.200
of Agha Shahid Ali"
Recently, she has been sending

01:18:37.200 --> 01:18:41.280
out two manuscripts, "How to
Make Your Mother Cry: Stories",

01:18:41.280 --> 01:18:45.430
and "Things People Say: A
Book of Essays" She teaches

01:18:45.430 --> 01:18:48.870
at Writers and Books, a
community-based literary center

01:18:48.870 --> 01:18:51.920
in Rochester, New York,
and serves as the co-chair

01:18:51.920 --> 01:18:53.220
of Kundiman North East.

01:18:53.220 --> 01:18:55.510
Everybody welcome Sejal.

01:18:55.510 --> 01:19:19.070
[ Applause ]

01:19:19.070 --> 01:19:20.370
&gt;&gt; Sejal Shah: I always
have a lot of stuff.

01:19:20.370 --> 01:19:21.670
Can you hear me?

01:19:21.670 --> 01:19:24.210
OK, I'm going to be
reading from "Mad Heart,

01:19:24.210 --> 01:19:29.760
Be Brave" which is edited
by Kazim Ali, and its essays

01:19:29.760 --> 01:19:32.910
on the poetry of
Agha Shahid Ali.

01:19:32.910 --> 01:19:36.130
First, I wanted to thank
also the organizers

01:19:36.130 --> 01:19:40.670
of the conference, to Lawrence,
the Smithsonian, to Kundiman,

01:19:40.670 --> 01:19:45.150
to Sara and Cathy, especially.

01:19:45.150 --> 01:19:49.280
Kundiman welcomed me as a
fellow in poetry five years ago,

01:19:49.280 --> 01:19:52.360
even though I did
an MFA in fiction,

01:19:52.360 --> 01:19:55.170
but my background is also poet,

01:19:55.170 --> 01:19:58.770
so this was before there
was a fiction retreat,

01:19:58.770 --> 01:20:01.100
but Kundiman also
changed my life.

01:20:01.100 --> 01:20:05.270
To Kaya, and to Nila, to the
Asian American Writers Workshop

01:20:05.270 --> 01:20:09.950
and [inaudible] to the
Library of Congress

01:20:09.950 --> 01:20:13.480
and [inaudible] Casper, to the
Asian American Literary Review,

01:20:13.480 --> 01:20:16.590
and to the discipline of
Asian American Studies,

01:20:16.590 --> 01:20:20.310
which saved during my
MFA, and to Kundiman

01:20:20.310 --> 01:20:22.380
which has been a home for
me these past five years,

01:20:22.380 --> 01:20:24.940
and thanks to all of
you for being here.

01:20:32.070 --> 01:20:41.720
I'm going to take a picture
of you [laughter], smile!

01:20:41.720 --> 01:20:43.110
This is amazing [laughter].

01:20:43.110 --> 01:20:50.730
So, a special shout-out to
[inaudible] from the Margins

01:20:50.730 --> 01:20:53.580
for editing and publishing
the original essay.

01:20:53.580 --> 01:20:57.190
And it's based on my remarks

01:20:57.190 --> 01:21:04.220
at Shahid's memorial,
[inaudible] in 2002.

01:21:04.220 --> 01:21:12.080
This is for my grandmother.

01:21:12.080 --> 01:21:17.170
Also, get your library
to order this [laughter].

01:21:17.170 --> 01:21:21.920
The title's called "The
World is Full of Paper,

01:21:21.920 --> 01:21:26.050
Write to Me" You might recognize
those words from Shahid's poem

01:21:26.050 --> 01:21:31.780
"Stationery", and if you
haven't read it, you should.

01:21:31.780 --> 01:21:36.810
Shahid was the first and only
person to call me a yankee.

01:21:36.810 --> 01:21:40.860
I first met Shahid in 1996
at Harvard University.

01:21:40.860 --> 01:21:45.150
It was a winter evening,
in my memory,

01:21:45.150 --> 01:21:48.400
Shahid wears a narrowed
jacket, something pale in color,

01:21:48.400 --> 01:21:53.930
and he glows the ways snow
glows on certain winter nights.

01:21:53.930 --> 01:21:56.290
He read from his
collection, "The Country

01:21:56.290 --> 01:21:59.600
without A Post Office", which
held the political violence

01:21:59.600 --> 01:22:03.100
in Kashmir in its backdrop.

01:22:03.100 --> 01:22:07.160
Afterwards, I told Shahid I
had applied to the MFA program

01:22:07.160 --> 01:22:10.310
at [inaudible] and that I
hoped to study with him.

01:22:10.310 --> 01:22:13.140
-- Come, come -- he said.

01:22:13.140 --> 01:22:17.750
Shahid was warm,
charismatic, irreverent,

01:22:17.750 --> 01:22:20.970
I fell for him the way you fall
for someone across the room

01:22:20.970 --> 01:22:25.410
at a party and then feel
compelled to approach.

01:22:25.410 --> 01:22:30.690
As soon as I saw and heard him
in Cambridge, I was transfixed.

01:22:30.690 --> 01:22:33.360
My name was a part of his name,

01:22:33.360 --> 01:22:35.770
I decided it was
destiny [laughter].

01:22:37.790 --> 01:22:39.550
Knowing almost nothing
about Kashmir

01:22:39.550 --> 01:22:43.070
and the Indian military
occupation, I thought of Shahid

01:22:43.070 --> 01:22:45.690
as simply an Indian
American writer.

01:22:45.690 --> 01:22:47.890
I hoped to find in him a mentor.

01:22:47.890 --> 01:22:52.430
At the time, I had met only
one other South Asian writer,

01:22:52.430 --> 01:22:57.600
Bharati Mukherjee, who declared
herself an American writer only,

01:22:57.600 --> 01:22:59.600
rejecting any hyphen
or descriptor

01:22:59.600 --> 01:23:02.980
such as Indian American
or South Asian,

01:23:02.980 --> 01:23:06.460
Bengali American,
or Asian American.

01:23:06.460 --> 01:23:10.610
She wished to be understood and
accepted as an American writer,

01:23:10.610 --> 01:23:12.250
as American as anyone else.

01:23:12.250 --> 01:23:15.520
I couldn't blame her.

01:23:16.840 --> 01:23:20.200
When I arrived in [inaudible]
in the fall of 1997,

01:23:20.200 --> 01:23:24.360
I immediately asked Shahid if I
could take his poetry workshop.

01:23:24.360 --> 01:23:26.700
Although I was a
fiction student,

01:23:26.700 --> 01:23:30.100
Shahid said -- Sure, why not?

01:23:31.410 --> 01:23:33.660
-- Don't worry, it's
only five pages.

01:23:33.660 --> 01:23:35.930
That was the first.

01:23:35.930 --> 01:23:39.540
Shahid often rewrote our poems,
starting from the bottom,

01:23:39.540 --> 01:23:42.450
working his way to the top.

01:23:42.450 --> 01:23:44.930
He suggested new
possibilities for each of us,

01:23:44.930 --> 01:23:48.110
reading his revisions
in a lilting voice.

01:23:48.110 --> 01:23:52.450
This rewriting occasionally
hurt my feelings [laughter],

01:23:52.450 --> 01:23:57.020
often bewildered me, and
mostly infuriated me [laughter]

01:23:57.020 --> 01:24:00.850
In my poem "Alexander Street",

01:24:00.850 --> 01:24:04.730
the first line became
"Instead the 28th".

01:24:04.730 --> 01:24:08.530
Shahid crossed out so many
lines in another poem that out

01:24:08.530 --> 01:24:15.290
of 25 lines only eight remained
[laughter] There are copies

01:24:15.290 --> 01:24:23.900
of his comments on my workshop
poems in the book, and yes,

01:24:23.900 --> 01:24:28.400
here's another that
got reordered.

01:24:28.400 --> 01:24:31.130
I never sent these out.

01:24:31.130 --> 01:24:34.850
Rob was in that workshop
with me.

01:24:34.850 --> 01:24:40.240
I've never read this with
someone else who was there too.

01:24:40.240 --> 01:24:42.380
I was horrified.

01:24:42.380 --> 01:24:45.070
In college, my poems have
received every literary

01:24:45.070 --> 01:24:47.710
prize awarded.

01:24:47.710 --> 01:24:50.610
No one had taken my
writing apart line by line,

01:24:50.610 --> 01:24:54.420
and dismantled their basic
architecture, what I thought

01:24:54.420 --> 01:24:58.860
of as the poem's
intention and integrity.

01:24:58.860 --> 01:25:03.580
Still, I could see that Shahid
was doing something interesting.

01:25:03.580 --> 01:25:07.560
I must've realized that I needed
to pay attention because even

01:25:07.560 --> 01:25:11.810
after 15 years, after almost
20 years, I had still held

01:25:11.810 --> 01:25:16.830
on to all of Shahid's
written comments on my work.

01:25:18.320 --> 01:25:21.180
One month into the semester,
Shahid delivered a piece

01:25:21.180 --> 01:25:26.270
of advice to me, announced
to our entire workshop,

01:25:26.270 --> 01:25:28.640
"Never use the word 'soul'
in a poem" [laughter],

01:25:28.640 --> 01:25:33.520
he declared and then grinned.

01:25:33.520 --> 01:25:37.650
He was both teasing
and completely serious.

01:25:37.650 --> 01:25:44.890
I winced, I had just brought in
a villanelle, "Onyx, Obsidian,

01:25:44.890 --> 01:25:47.780
Flocks, Coal", in
which "soul" was one

01:25:47.780 --> 01:25:49.580
of the repeating end words --

01:25:49.580 --> 01:25:56.180
[ Laughter ]

01:25:56.180 --> 01:25:59.640
3 [Laughter] I have remembered
his dictum through the years

01:25:59.640 --> 01:26:03.210
and have heard myself saying
it to my own students.

01:26:03.210 --> 01:26:07.490
We want our poems and stories to
be soulful to possess qualities

01:26:07.490 --> 01:26:11.200
of the infinite in them, but
it's difficult for the word

01:26:11.200 --> 01:26:14.970
"soul" to do the
work of that desire.

01:26:14.970 --> 01:26:17.830
Though miff by his
handling of my poems,

01:26:17.830 --> 01:26:21.500
where was the unadulterated
praise?

01:26:21.500 --> 01:26:25.580
[Laughter] I was, like everyone
else, still taken by Shahid,

01:26:25.580 --> 01:26:30.160
admiring both his exquisite
poetry, and his generous nature.

01:26:32.080 --> 01:26:34.400
In workshop, he recited
each of our names

01:26:34.400 --> 01:26:37.710
as though it were a poem,
brilliant, somehow miraculous,

01:26:37.710 --> 01:26:41.690
and mysterious, complete
in and of itself.

01:26:41.690 --> 01:26:47.450
It's the wonderful Carry St
George Comer, Andrew Varnon,

01:26:47.450 --> 01:26:55.170
Robert M Casper, Daniel Hales.

01:26:55.170 --> 01:26:58.230
Twice that fall he invited
our class and other friends

01:26:58.230 --> 01:27:01.410
and admirers for sprawling
dinner parties, people spilled

01:27:01.410 --> 01:27:03.420
over from room to room.

01:27:03.420 --> 01:27:06.600
When I offered to cook,
Shahid laughed and said,

01:27:06.600 --> 01:27:09.600
"You American-born Indians
are the most terrible cooks"

01:27:09.600 --> 01:27:17.410
[laughter] I was taken
aback, but had to laugh.

01:27:17.410 --> 01:27:20.240
One evening when the stove
burners were not working,

01:27:20.240 --> 01:27:23.130
and the food had to be
warmed up somewhere else,

01:27:23.130 --> 01:27:27.100
Shahid charmed us for hours,
as only a good host could,

01:27:27.100 --> 01:27:31.390
playing Hindi film
music, and ABBA.

01:27:31.390 --> 01:27:35.750
Why not? The perfect
Shahidian combination.

01:27:35.750 --> 01:27:38.220
No one minded not
eating for a while,

01:27:38.220 --> 01:27:40.790
we may not have even noticed.

01:27:40.790 --> 01:27:43.460
He broke into songs.

01:27:43.460 --> 01:27:45.290
-- Hey -- I said --
I know that song --

01:27:45.290 --> 01:27:47.850
and began dancing the
Barathanatyam steps I had

01:27:47.850 --> 01:27:50.150
learned as a child.

01:27:51.510 --> 01:28:03.510
[ Sings ]

01:28:03.510 --> 01:28:09.630
[ Applause ]

01:28:09.630 --> 01:28:12.290
Shahid clapped his hands
in encouragement, --

01:28:12.290 --> 01:28:14.630
Bha, bha -- he said finally.

01:28:14.630 --> 01:28:17.470
The subcontinental applause
I had sought [laughter]

01:28:17.470 --> 01:28:18.770
finally [laughter].

01:28:18.770 --> 01:28:28.860
In my copy of "The Country
without A Post Office",

01:28:28.860 --> 01:28:32.100
he filled the entire front
page with his effusive script

01:28:32.100 --> 01:28:39.700
in blue fountain pen ink, "For
Sajel M. Shah, Shah of shahs.

01:28:39.700 --> 01:28:42.980
So royal, so princely.

01:28:42.980 --> 01:28:45.850
So regal, dash.

01:28:45.850 --> 01:28:49.780
So, she who couldn't go to
Spain is going to Italy, ah!

01:28:49.780 --> 01:28:54.920
He decorated this note with
long dashes flourishing

01:28:54.920 --> 01:28:56.720
on either side of the "ah!"

01:28:56.720 --> 01:28:59.680
spanning the width of the page.

01:28:59.680 --> 01:29:01.790
Later he continued
in another pen,

01:29:01.790 --> 01:29:03.710
"and now where is the lipstick?

01:29:03.710 --> 01:29:05.850
Purple of color.

01:29:05.850 --> 01:29:07.470
Sajel has the magic".

01:29:07.470 --> 01:29:11.380
Who else could have written
about the purple lipstick I wore

01:29:11.380 --> 01:29:14.430
that year in a way that
transformed my name,

01:29:14.430 --> 01:29:18.130
travel plans, and shade of
lipstick into near poetry?

01:29:18.130 --> 01:29:21.770
It was what we all wanted, what
anyone wants from someone he

01:29:21.770 --> 01:29:25.240
or she admires, and
certainly what I wanted,

01:29:25.240 --> 01:29:29.480
for them to see the
magic that is only you.

01:29:29.480 --> 01:29:33.450
As a professor and teacher
myself now for many years,

01:29:33.450 --> 01:29:39.180
I understand his rewriting,
as painful as it was for me,

01:29:39.180 --> 01:29:44.980
as another form of attention,
even as another kind of love.

01:29:44.980 --> 01:29:50.390
It is a strategy I use too
in the workshops I now teach.

01:29:50.390 --> 01:29:54.500
Shahid was trying to lessen
my dependence on narrative,

01:29:56.130 --> 01:30:00.010
my desire to tell a
story within a poem

01:30:00.010 --> 01:30:01.310
And to instead allow the
poem to unfold, to breathe,

01:30:01.310 --> 01:30:02.610
to live through the generation
of lyrics possibilities.

01:30:02.610 --> 01:30:03.910
During my first year of
graduate school I had reason

01:30:03.910 --> 01:30:05.210
to call Shahid once
or twice at home.

01:30:05.210 --> 01:30:06.510
His answering machine
message was simply,

01:30:06.510 --> 01:30:07.810
"I knew you'd call" [laughter]
The first time I heard it,

01:30:07.810 --> 01:30:09.110
I hung up [laughter] Shahid had,
as usual, caught me off guard.

01:30:09.110 --> 01:30:10.410
His voice left me
speechless and smiling.

01:30:10.410 --> 01:30:11.710
Shahid's message
was to-the-point

01:30:11.710 --> 01:30:13.010
and too short, like his life.

01:30:13.010 --> 01:30:14.310
We flocked to him, poets and
writers, ambitious dreamers.

01:30:14.310 --> 01:30:15.610
I see him in his
kitchen turning toward me

01:30:15.610 --> 01:30:16.910
in a royal blue sweater,

01:30:16.910 --> 01:30:18.210
his shirt sleeves
unbuttoned and pushed back.

01:30:18.210 --> 01:30:19.510
He is cooking for us.

01:30:19.510 --> 01:30:20.810
I've snapped a photo and caught
him off guard in the picture,

01:30:20.810 --> 01:30:22.110
but he's still posing,
still gesturing,

01:30:22.110 --> 01:30:23.410
still lovely, still young.

01:30:23.410 --> 01:30:24.710
He would probably
hate me saying so.

01:30:24.710 --> 01:30:26.010
He would hate me saying so,

01:30:26.010 --> 01:30:27.310
but I think his eyes
looked soulful [inaudible]

01:30:27.310 --> 01:30:28.610
"I knew you'd call"

01:30:28.610 --> 01:30:29.910
[ Laughter ]

01:30:29.910 --> 01:30:31.710
The first time I
heard it, I hang up.

01:30:31.710 --> 01:30:35.160
[ Laughter ]

01:30:35.160 --> 01:30:38.420
Shahid had as usual
caught me out of guard,

01:30:38.420 --> 01:30:41.940
his voice left me
speechless, and smiling.

01:30:43.120 --> 01:30:47.680
Shahid was to the point and
too short, like in his life,

01:30:47.680 --> 01:30:51.090
we [inaudible] poems and
writers, ambitious dreamers.

01:30:51.090 --> 01:30:55.050
I see him in his
kitchen turning toward me

01:30:55.050 --> 01:30:58.600
in a royal blue sweater, his
short sleeves unbuttoned,

01:30:58.600 --> 01:31:02.690
and pushed back,
he's cooking for us.

01:31:02.690 --> 01:31:06.060
I snapped a photo and caught
him unguard in the picture,

01:31:06.060 --> 01:31:09.240
but he still posing,
still gesturing,

01:31:09.240 --> 01:31:12.140
still lovely, still young.

01:31:12.140 --> 01:31:16.660
He would probably hate me saying
so, he would hate me saying so,

01:31:16.660 --> 01:31:19.720
but I think his eyes
looked so fool [phonetic].

01:31:20.780 --> 01:31:23.510
I knew you'd call.

01:31:23.510 --> 01:31:37.070
