01:35:43.760 --> 01:35:46.250
for the National Book
Festival when I first started

01:35:46.250 --> 01:35:50.340
at the Library of Congress,
back in 2011, I'm so happy

01:35:50.340 --> 01:35:52.990
to welcome her today
to this festival.

01:35:52.990 --> 01:35:55.510
Please join me in
welcoming Kimiko Hahn.

01:35:55.510 --> 01:36:09.380
[ Applause ]

01:36:09.380 --> 01:36:11.230
&gt;&gt; Kimiko Hahn: Oh, thank you.

01:36:11.230 --> 01:36:13.320
Thank you, Rob.

01:36:13.320 --> 01:36:14.660
Not just been a year.

01:36:14.660 --> 01:36:19.500
I think at least one decade,
if not one and a half, or so.

01:36:27.870 --> 01:36:33.470
Alone with everyone else who
has else spoken and read,

01:36:33.470 --> 01:36:38.330
I too feel honored, and
thankful, and especially

01:36:38.330 --> 01:36:43.720
to Lawrence and Lisa,
and Rob, and Hanya,

01:36:43.720 --> 01:36:45.520
let's all celebrate them.

01:36:45.520 --> 01:36:55.690
[ Applause ]

01:36:55.690 --> 01:36:58.430
And also thank you to
all the organizations

01:36:58.430 --> 01:37:01.680
and the other people
who made this a reality.

01:37:01.680 --> 01:37:07.810
It's just incredible,
and brilliant.

01:37:07.810 --> 01:37:12.140
What an urgent time
for a radical soul,

01:37:12.140 --> 01:37:16.020
what a time to reaffirm
that our histories are

01:37:16.020 --> 01:37:22.810
that of obedient Orientals, in
fact, not any kind of Oriental.

01:37:22.810 --> 01:37:27.620
We carved protect poems on the
walls of our detention center.

01:37:27.620 --> 01:37:32.910
We rebelled against the lunas in
a field of vulcanic back soil.

01:37:32.910 --> 01:37:36.910
We protested when forced to live
in a horse stall, we said, "No,

01:37:36.910 --> 01:37:42.270
and So" You also volunteered
for the Armed Services

01:37:42.270 --> 01:37:53.280
to prove patriotism forming the
42nd Infantery Regiment Combat

01:37:53.280 --> 01:37:58.290
Team, which I think
my uncle was in,

01:37:58.290 --> 01:38:04.600
the most decorated unit US
history is "go-for-broke".

01:38:04.600 --> 01:38:09.300
We embroil it, we were born
right here, we assimilate it,

01:38:09.300 --> 01:38:12.620
and we challenge the
assimilation as paradigm.

01:38:12.620 --> 01:38:17.590
What a radical moment
for us to be together.

01:38:17.590 --> 01:38:22.330
Over the past several elections,
candidates have either connected

01:38:22.330 --> 01:38:25.550
or missed grassroots movements.

01:38:25.550 --> 01:38:30.630
Yes, grassroot organizing
again, for the basics,

01:38:30.630 --> 01:38:34.350
from loading rights
to immigration rights

01:38:34.350 --> 01:38:38.210
to healthcare, I'm
so honored to be here

01:38:38.210 --> 01:38:42.530
at Smithsonian Asian
Pacific American Center,

01:38:42.530 --> 01:38:47.560
and also the Library of
Congress, the Apex mission is

01:38:47.560 --> 01:38:52.690
to be a cultural laboratory
envisioning [inaudible]

01:38:52.690 --> 01:38:56.140
as a form of community
organizing.

01:38:56.140 --> 01:38:59.810
That is so brilliant,
I love that.

01:38:59.810 --> 01:39:03.380
I'm going to say it again,
[inaudible] as a form

01:39:03.380 --> 01:39:06.210
of community organizing.

01:39:06.210 --> 01:39:08.960
Thank you.

01:39:08.960 --> 01:39:13.030
Our former Poet Laureate
Juan Felipe Herrera said

01:39:13.030 --> 01:39:17.330
of his own coming-of-age,
and offbeat education --

01:39:17.330 --> 01:39:19.750
"Listening to the
poets around and ahead

01:39:19.750 --> 01:39:22.040
of me, I was taking note.

01:39:22.040 --> 01:39:27.900
So, you know, society was our
workshop" I've been invited

01:39:27.900 --> 01:39:30.580
to give a sense of
our collective story

01:39:30.580 --> 01:39:34.520
from my personal, and
modest point of view.

01:39:36.180 --> 01:39:41.530
How unlikely that a little
Eurasian girl, you know,

01:39:41.530 --> 01:39:43.990
[inaudible] born and
isolated in Pleasantville,

01:39:43.990 --> 01:39:47.800
New York would be
here to address you.

01:39:47.800 --> 01:39:53.050
Thankfully, I came of age
in the 1960's and 70's.

01:39:53.050 --> 01:39:56.370
Thankfully, after a year
living in the Japan,

01:39:56.370 --> 01:39:58.530
my parents enrolled
my sister and me

01:39:58.530 --> 01:40:03.110
into Japanese language classes,
and Japanese dance lessons,

01:40:03.110 --> 01:40:07.950
at the New York Buddhist Church
on Riverside Drive in Manhattan.

01:40:07.950 --> 01:40:10.050
How could my parents have known

01:40:10.050 --> 01:40:15.190
that in dance class I'd meet
Aichi Kochiyama and come

01:40:15.190 --> 01:40:17.550
to know her radical family.

01:40:17.550 --> 01:40:22.390
Her mother, Yuri Kochiyama, well
known for her radical politics,

01:40:22.390 --> 01:40:27.750
held the dying Malcom X
in the Audubon Ballroom,

01:40:27.750 --> 01:40:31.420
Saturdays in the city
were my workshop.

01:40:33.320 --> 01:40:37.030
By high school, I was pretty
steep in Japanese culture,

01:40:37.030 --> 01:40:40.770
more than most Asian
Americans of my generation.

01:40:40.770 --> 01:40:45.260
My politics were
limited to rock and roll.

01:40:45.260 --> 01:40:50.180
Not too shabby if you consider
ten soldiers and Nixon coming

01:40:50.180 --> 01:40:56.140
for dead in Ohio, and we
don't need to escalate.

01:40:56.140 --> 01:41:01.930
You see, war is not the answer,
for only love can conquer hate,

01:41:01.930 --> 01:41:04.490
but how could my
parents have figured

01:41:04.490 --> 01:41:07.410
that after dance class I
would hang out in the dojo

01:41:07.410 --> 01:41:11.660
with the judo boys, or as
Grace Jones would purr,

01:41:11.660 --> 01:41:15.830
"checking out the race"
[laughter] And, by the way,

01:41:15.830 --> 01:41:20.670
I'm really envious that
Karen had photographs.

01:41:20.670 --> 01:41:24.400
Mei-mei and I were quite the
hotties back then [laughter]

01:41:24.400 --> 01:41:28.210
and I wish we had
had picture of us!

01:41:28.210 --> 01:41:34.200
So, I'm sorry, next time
[laughter][inaudible] So,

01:41:34.200 --> 01:41:39.100
thank you [laughter] I
was fishing, wasn't I?

01:41:40.720 --> 01:41:42.470
[Laughter] So, getting
back to checking

01:41:42.470 --> 01:41:46.290
out the race [laughter],
enter a young man,

01:41:46.290 --> 01:41:49.210
a Japanese American radical
whose mother had been

01:41:49.210 --> 01:41:54.630
incarcerated in the infamous
Topaz War Relocation camp.

01:41:54.630 --> 01:41:58.780
Dating him, I hung out at
Chinatown food co-op meetings

01:41:58.780 --> 01:42:01.720
with the likes of Peter
Quang [phonetic] and sat

01:42:01.720 --> 01:42:07.130
in on Marxist study groups,
and culture was never marginal.

01:42:07.130 --> 01:42:11.590
The city on Saturdays
is where I felt alive.

01:42:11.590 --> 01:42:16.370
In 1970, the basement workshop
on Elizabeth Street was opened

01:42:16.370 --> 01:42:20.630
by artists such as Tomie
Arai, a distant relative

01:42:20.630 --> 01:42:24.720
as it turned out, and
writers such as Fay Chiang.

01:42:24.720 --> 01:42:29.780
Here are the opening stanzas
from Fay's poem "Chinatown".

01:42:38.040 --> 01:42:41.900
"Mahjong and dice on the tables
upstairs, confusion of trucks,

01:42:41.900 --> 01:42:46.120
and cars, and calls, and
children, and cats, and dogs,

01:42:46.120 --> 01:42:51.860
and stream of people falling
off the mountain of gold.

01:42:51.860 --> 01:42:55.580
Eddie died yesterday, another
street kid shot his fucking

01:42:55.580 --> 01:42:59.870
brains out and Eddie's
in heaven east river.

01:42:59.870 --> 01:43:03.870
Did you know about Mrs. Tong
jumped off a building looking

01:43:03.870 --> 01:43:07.070
for peace six stories
above mott?

01:43:07.070 --> 01:43:11.600
And hey, old Louie just passed
away in his sleep, the fool,

01:43:11.600 --> 01:43:15.250
sleeping with the
gas pipes on, again.

01:43:15.250 --> 01:43:16.740
Did you hear about Lee?

01:43:16.740 --> 01:43:18.760
that he couldn't take
his henpecking wife,

01:43:18.760 --> 01:43:22.250
and screaming babies, and
rotten kids, and his waiter job,

01:43:22.250 --> 01:43:25.610
and promises that couldn't
be bought with pennies

01:43:25.610 --> 01:43:32.070
that he split before
his head did?"

01:43:32.070 --> 01:43:35.770
From these Asian American
circles, I became acquainted

01:43:35.770 --> 01:43:37.950
with those on the West Coast.

01:43:37.950 --> 01:43:40.620
Not surprisingly, their
militancy was ahead

01:43:40.620 --> 01:43:42.960
of the movement in New York.

01:43:42.960 --> 01:43:46.440
There were poets such
as Mitsuye Yamada

01:43:46.440 --> 01:43:49.860
who wrote this poem
"Evacuation".

01:43:49.860 --> 01:43:55.550
As we boarded the bus,
bags on both sides,

01:43:55.550 --> 01:43:58.400
they'd never packed
two bags before

01:43:58.400 --> 01:44:01.700
on a vacation lasting forever.

01:44:01.700 --> 01:44:06.160
The Seattle Times
photographer said -- smile --

01:44:06.160 --> 01:44:08.350
so, obediently, I smiled.

01:44:08.350 --> 01:44:11.630
In the caption the next day read

01:44:11.630 --> 01:44:15.840
"Note smiling faces,
a lesson to Tokyo".

01:44:15.840 --> 01:44:22.250
And there was Nellie Wong,
here's an excerpt from "Away

01:44:22.250 --> 01:44:27.620
from The Blue Swans"
"Away, away from antlers,

01:44:27.620 --> 01:44:32.550
dried lizard necks hidden like
pearls in herbalist shells,

01:44:32.550 --> 01:44:36.520
women warbling Chinese
songs, their voices drifting

01:44:36.520 --> 01:44:42.280
out the hot summer air, hanging
onto men in grey felt hats

01:44:42.280 --> 01:44:46.890
with silver dollars dangling
in their pants' pockets.

01:44:46.890 --> 01:44:51.490
Crossing the boundaries to
the TMD on 11th in Broadway,

01:44:51.490 --> 01:44:56.410
past Jack's Footlong Hot Dogs,
smelling popcorn at the antics

01:44:56.410 --> 01:44:59.240
of Abbot and Costello.

01:44:59.240 --> 01:45:03.750
Arm in arm, our bravery slung
by our mother's warnings.

01:45:03.750 --> 01:45:07.780
Uptown to the paramount in
all it silver, and purple,

01:45:07.780 --> 01:45:11.270
and red velvet carpets
chewing spearmint

01:45:11.270 --> 01:45:13.690
through the double
feature and returning

01:45:13.690 --> 01:45:18.990
to Chinatown sucking preserved
plums, and agreeing to lie"

01:45:18.990 --> 01:45:23.860
And across the Pacific,
in the Hawaiian Islands

01:45:23.860 --> 01:45:27.890
of mother's birth, there was
burgeoning Asian American writer

01:45:27.890 --> 01:45:30.960
scene, and the group
"Bamboo Ridge",

01:45:30.960 --> 01:45:33.150
and here they are,
Bamboo Ridge, people.

01:45:33.150 --> 01:45:34.950
We love you!

01:45:34.950 --> 01:45:39.120
[ Applause ]

01:45:39.120 --> 01:45:43.230
One of the writers from the
same generation of poets

01:45:43.230 --> 01:45:48.030
who I just read was Juliet
Kono, and she's here.

01:45:48.030 --> 01:45:50.300
Juliet, I love you [laughter].

01:45:50.300 --> 01:45:54.600
And she had her very
excellent collection

01:45:54.600 --> 01:45:58.720
"Hilo Rains" published
as a double issue

01:45:58.720 --> 01:46:01.010
of Bamboo Ridge Journal.

01:46:01.010 --> 01:46:05.080
Please listen to this excerpt
from "Smoke: An Apostrophe

01:46:05.080 --> 01:46:07.380
to The Speaker's Mother".

01:46:08.540 --> 01:46:10.260
"You were 13.

01:46:10.260 --> 01:46:13.180
Your father has made
you quit school.

01:46:13.180 --> 01:46:16.900
You can no longer play
with the other girls.

01:46:16.900 --> 01:46:20.180
You must now cut
cane like a man,

01:46:20.180 --> 01:46:25.540
and every day you watch the
lunas burn adjacent field

01:46:25.540 --> 01:46:28.600
where yellow flames
crackle and lift high

01:46:28.600 --> 01:46:31.820
into smoke, filling your coughs.

01:46:31.820 --> 01:46:35.540
Soot rains, the skies
look overcast

01:46:35.540 --> 01:46:41.570
as if someone has tossed a throw
net over you and hauled you in,

01:46:41.570 --> 01:46:49.000
a good day's catch for the
next day's work, and the next."

01:46:49.000 --> 01:46:54.100
You may have noticed that every
poet who I've been reading

01:46:54.100 --> 01:46:58.680
so far are women, and that's
because these are the ones

01:46:58.680 --> 01:47:01.490
that in effect became
my mentors, so I'm going

01:47:01.490 --> 01:47:05.150
to continue in that vein.

01:47:05.150 --> 01:47:08.460
In concert with community
organizing, writers

01:47:08.460 --> 01:47:12.980
and educators published
newsletters, mimeographed,

01:47:12.980 --> 01:47:15.020
journals and anthologies,

01:47:15.020 --> 01:47:22.470
the first one I'd ever held was
[inaudible] published in 1974

01:47:22.470 --> 01:47:27.090
by [inaudible] and Sean Huang,

01:47:27.090 --> 01:47:31.500
I think Garrett called them
the gang of four yesterday.

01:47:31.500 --> 01:47:36.700
10 years later, Native American
Joseph Bruchac published an

01:47:36.700 --> 01:47:41.700
anthology of Asian American
poetry, "Breaking Silence".

01:47:41.700 --> 01:47:45.710
These anthologies became the
start of my self-education

01:47:45.710 --> 01:47:48.270
in Asian American poetry.

01:47:48.270 --> 01:47:53.840
The legendary West Coast radical
Janice Mirikitani opens her poem

01:47:53.840 --> 01:47:56.660
"Breaking Silence" with
the executive order

01:47:56.660 --> 01:48:01.340
"Take only what you can
carry" and she uses quotes

01:48:01.340 --> 01:48:04.470
from her mother's testimony
before the Commission

01:48:04.470 --> 01:48:07.360
on Wartime Relocation
and Internment

01:48:07.360 --> 01:48:10.820
of Japanese American Civilians.

01:48:10.820 --> 01:48:15.740
Here's an excerpt from
"Breaking Silence".

01:48:15.740 --> 01:48:21.570
"And then, all was
hushed for announcements.

01:48:21.570 --> 01:48:24.490
Take only what you can carry.

01:48:24.490 --> 01:48:28.100
We were made to believe
our faces betrayed us,

01:48:28.100 --> 01:48:32.360
our bodies were loud with
yellow screaming flesh,

01:48:32.360 --> 01:48:37.050
needing to be silenced
behind barbed wire.

01:48:37.050 --> 01:48:41.660
'Mr. Commissioner, it seems we
were singled out from others

01:48:41.660 --> 01:48:43.520
who are under suspicion.

01:48:43.520 --> 01:48:46.770
Our neighbors were of
German and Italian descent,

01:48:46.770 --> 01:48:49.180
some of whom were not citizens.

01:48:49.180 --> 01:48:55.040
It seems we were singled
out' She had worn her sweat

01:48:55.040 --> 01:48:59.230
like lemon leaves, shining
on the rough edges of work,

01:48:59.230 --> 01:49:01.890
removed the mirrors
from her room

01:49:01.890 --> 01:49:05.340
so she would not be
tempted by vanity.

01:49:05.340 --> 01:49:09.110
Her dreams honed the
blade of her plough.

01:49:09.110 --> 01:49:11.970
The land, the building
of food was noisy

01:49:11.970 --> 01:49:14.510
as the opening of irises.

01:49:14.510 --> 01:49:19.990
The sounds of work bolted
in barracks, silenced.

01:49:19.990 --> 01:49:24.100
'Mr. Commissioner, so when
you tell me I must limit my

01:49:24.100 --> 01:49:29.520
testimony to five minutes,
when you tell me my time is up,

01:49:29.520 --> 01:49:35.100
I tell you this -- pride has
kept my lips pinned by nails,

01:49:35.100 --> 01:49:41.470
my rage coffined, but I assume
my past, to claim this time,

01:49:41.470 --> 01:49:43.310
my youth is buried

01:49:43.310 --> 01:49:49.120
in [inaudible] ghost
visits Hamachi Gate,

01:49:49.120 --> 01:49:54.050
my niece haunts Tune Lake'
Words are better than tears,

01:49:54.050 --> 01:49:59.970
so I spilled on, I
killed this, the silence".

01:50:01.820 --> 01:50:03.120
No surprise that many

01:50:03.120 --> 01:50:06.590
in the movement didn't
consider a biracial poet truly

01:50:06.590 --> 01:50:08.150
Asian American.

01:50:08.150 --> 01:50:13.570
I wasn't completely at home in
those circles, not completely.

01:50:13.570 --> 01:50:20.140
So, determined to learn my
craft, I put in undergrad time

01:50:20.140 --> 01:50:22.450
at the University of Iowa.

01:50:22.450 --> 01:50:25.380
There I studied with
Marvin Bell, Louise Glück,

01:50:25.380 --> 01:50:30.550
Charles Wright, and the then
graduate student, Rita Dove.

01:50:30.550 --> 01:50:33.490
These were radiant
workshops, and they were also,

01:50:33.490 --> 01:50:36.260
except for Rita,
pretty darn white.

01:50:36.260 --> 01:50:40.830
From there, I returned to New
York to find more of myself.

01:50:40.830 --> 01:50:44.540
Poets were reciting poems
on the street and continuing

01:50:44.540 --> 01:50:47.610
to ally themselves
with social issues.

01:50:47.610 --> 01:50:50.320
Pedro Pietri, one of
the original founder

01:50:50.320 --> 01:50:52.590
of the Nuyorican Poets Café,

01:50:52.590 --> 01:50:55.850
handed out poems written
on condom wrappers.

01:50:55.850 --> 01:50:59.140
This is before the AIDS crisis.

01:50:59.140 --> 01:51:02.620
Louis Reyes Rivera told me
more than once, "Kimiko,

01:51:02.620 --> 01:51:07.400
take your palm off the damn
page" The city was again

01:51:07.400 --> 01:51:08.920
my workshop.

01:51:08.920 --> 01:51:12.570
I would also meet
radical feminists

01:51:12.570 --> 01:51:15.190
like Patricia Spears Jones,

01:51:15.190 --> 01:51:18.610
Sandra Esteves, and
Frances Chung.

01:51:18.610 --> 01:51:22.580
From Frances, posthumously
published, "Crazy Melon

01:51:22.580 --> 01:51:27.300
and Chinese Apple" a
poem, "Double Ten".

01:51:28.490 --> 01:51:32.500
"Early morning, the Sunday
sound of an accordion.

01:51:32.500 --> 01:51:35.690
A conversation with
two Ukrainian women

01:51:35.690 --> 01:51:40.020
about calling the plumber,
taking baths in our kitchens.

01:51:40.020 --> 01:51:45.130
You like the green
stone around my neck.

01:51:45.130 --> 01:51:46.430
Later on, the [inaudible],

01:51:46.430 --> 01:51:50.730
a black man struggling along
singing a Chinatown ballad

01:51:50.730 --> 01:51:53.590
as I sing one of Philly's songs.

01:51:53.590 --> 01:51:57.820
In her kitchen, warmer
than mine, a strong smell

01:51:57.820 --> 01:52:05.030
of black mushrooms" In
1981 I organized a panel

01:52:05.030 --> 01:52:09.530
of Asian American writers for
the National Writer's Congress,

01:52:09.530 --> 01:52:12.650
sponsored by the
Nation Institute,

01:52:12.650 --> 01:52:14.800
just the Nation Magazine,

01:52:14.800 --> 01:52:18.050
I believed those genuinely
liberal writers didn't truly

01:52:18.050 --> 01:52:22.480
comprehend the depth and
turbulence that would simmer up,

01:52:22.480 --> 01:52:26.150
especially by so-called
minority writers.

01:52:26.150 --> 01:52:30.010
Not only did I meet
Jessica Hagedorn,

01:52:30.010 --> 01:52:33.770
[inaudible] I connected with
poet comrades, Luis Rodriguez

01:52:33.770 --> 01:52:38.100
who would go on to
found Tia Chucha Press

01:52:38.100 --> 01:52:42.110
and Community Center, and
also Michael Ward who is now

01:52:42.110 --> 01:52:44.790
at the African Diaspora Museum.

01:52:44.790 --> 01:52:48.740
And later Jessica invited me
to read at Basement Workshop,

01:52:48.740 --> 01:52:52.770
yay [laughter] How could I
have known just how cool it was

01:52:52.770 --> 01:52:54.710
to be the warmup
act for [inaudible],

01:52:54.710 --> 01:52:59.580
who at that moment
became a fast friend?

01:52:59.580 --> 01:53:04.650
For starters, we organized
political cabaret in Harlem.

01:53:12.200 --> 01:53:17.020
Around this time too, there was
a changing aesthetic in the air.

01:53:17.020 --> 01:53:22.120
Jessica's pet foods and tropical
apparitions would present

01:53:22.120 --> 01:53:26.750
in print the kind of lyrics
she sassed out in the clubs.

01:53:26.750 --> 01:53:29.470
Her poetic voice
would later grow

01:53:29.470 --> 01:53:33.050
into characters from her novel.

01:53:33.050 --> 01:53:37.180
Here's the last two stanzas from
the poem "I Went All the Way

01:53:37.180 --> 01:53:41.250
Out Here Looking for You, Bob
Marley" [laughter] written

01:53:41.250 --> 01:53:43.340
with the endnote
"Kingston, Jamaica,

01:53:43.340 --> 01:53:50.950
1977" "And this just isn't fair

01:53:50.950 --> 01:53:54.500
because you are the
only one I trust.

01:53:54.500 --> 01:53:56.160
I have to know.

01:53:56.160 --> 01:53:59.350
Were you shot in the
arm, like they said?

01:53:59.350 --> 01:54:04.270
And don't they know they
can't kill music like that?

01:54:04.270 --> 01:54:08.620
They should heed from
America and relegate you

01:54:08.620 --> 01:54:12.440
to the Sheraton Hotel's
Junkanoo Lounge

01:54:12.440 --> 01:54:14.100
as a malnourished [inaudible].

01:54:14.100 --> 01:54:21.240
And this just isn't fair because
you are the only one I trust,

01:54:21.240 --> 01:54:23.650
and I haven't even met you yet,

01:54:23.650 --> 01:54:30.340
and I am waiting" There
was a continuing debate

01:54:30.340 --> 01:54:34.020
on whether one had to write
about Asian American issues

01:54:34.020 --> 01:54:36.660
to be an Asian American writer.

01:54:36.660 --> 01:54:40.860
Thank heaven for Mei-mei
and her innovative spirit.

01:54:40.860 --> 01:54:44.770
You will hear her later, but
meantime here's an excerpt

01:54:44.770 --> 01:54:48.840
from -- a newer poem
than back in the day,

01:54:48.840 --> 01:54:51.050
it's an excerpt from, "Hello,

01:54:51.050 --> 01:54:57.070
the Roses" "The rose
communicates instantly

01:54:57.070 --> 01:55:01.480
with the woman by sight,
collapsing its boundaries,

01:55:01.480 --> 01:55:05.480
and the woman widens
her boundaries.

01:55:05.480 --> 01:55:12.430
Her rate of perception slows
down, because of its complexity.

01:55:12.430 --> 01:55:16.750
There's a feeling of touching
and being touched, the shadings

01:55:16.750 --> 01:55:20.640
of color she can
sense from touch.

01:55:20.640 --> 01:55:27.410
There's an affinity between
awareness and blossom."

01:55:27.410 --> 01:55:30.330
Thank the heavens too

01:55:30.330 --> 01:55:36.610
for lending us Theresa Hak Kyung
Cha whose Avant Gard polyphonic

01:55:36.610 --> 01:55:41.410
cross-genre "Dictee"
was published in 1982,

01:55:41.410 --> 01:55:43.840
the same year she was murdered.

01:55:43.840 --> 01:55:48.260
Here's an excerpt.

01:55:48.260 --> 01:55:51.230
"She would take on
their punctuation.

01:55:51.230 --> 01:55:54.360
She waits to service this.

01:55:54.360 --> 01:55:57.330
Theirs. Punctuation.

01:55:57.330 --> 01:56:02.190
She would become,
herself, demarcations.

01:56:02.190 --> 01:56:03.830
Absorb it.

01:56:03.830 --> 01:56:08.570
Spill it. Seize upon
the punctuation.

01:56:08.570 --> 01:56:11.800
Last air. Give her.

01:56:11.800 --> 01:56:14.240
Her. The relay.

01:56:14.240 --> 01:56:16.630
Voice. Assign.

01:56:16.630 --> 01:56:19.420
Hand it. Deliver it.

01:56:19.420 --> 01:56:26.190
Deliver." Cha was a
first-generation Korean.

01:56:26.190 --> 01:56:29.970
Of course, all along, different
waves of immigrants mixed

01:56:29.970 --> 01:56:35.560
into the Asian American groups
of 2nd, 3rd, 4th generations.

01:56:35.560 --> 01:56:40.000
Two of those brilliant writers,
[inaudible] who came here,

01:56:40.000 --> 01:56:44.970
who was born in Kerala, in
Southern India, and came here.

01:56:44.970 --> 01:56:48.970
And Miomi Kim, who of course
was born in Seoul, Korea.

01:56:57.570 --> 01:57:01.780
Myong and Mei-mei unlike some of
the other poets I've read broke

01:57:01.780 --> 01:57:04.840
through into the MFA scene.

01:57:04.840 --> 01:57:08.710
Then, along came Marilyn.

01:57:08.710 --> 01:57:14.150
"I am Marilyn Mei Ling Chin.

01:57:14.150 --> 01:57:16.870
Oh, how I love the resoluteness

01:57:16.870 --> 01:57:20.510
of that first-person
singular followed

01:57:20.510 --> 01:57:24.930
by that stalwart
indicative of "be",

01:57:24.930 --> 01:57:29.890
without the uncertain
i-n-g of "becoming."

01:57:29.890 --> 01:57:33.630
Of course, the name had
been changed somewhere

01:57:33.630 --> 01:57:38.070
between Angel Island and
the sea, when my father,

01:57:38.070 --> 01:57:44.840
the paper son in the late 1950s,
obsessed with a bombshell blond,

01:57:44.840 --> 01:57:49.660
transliterated "Mei
Ling" to "Marilyn."

01:57:49.660 --> 01:57:53.950
And nobody dared question
his initial impulse,

01:57:53.950 --> 01:57:58.300
for we all know lust
drove men to greatness,

01:57:58.300 --> 01:58:02.190
not goodness, not decency.

01:58:02.190 --> 01:58:05.960
And there I was, a
wayward pink baby,

01:58:05.960 --> 01:58:09.190
named after some tragic
white woman swollen

01:58:09.190 --> 01:58:12.140
with gin and Nembutal.

01:58:12.140 --> 01:58:15.660
My mother couldn't
pronounce the "r."

01:58:15.660 --> 01:58:22.310
She dubbed me "Numba one
female offshoot" for brevity:

01:58:22.310 --> 01:58:26.760
henceforth, she will live
and die in sublime ignorance,

01:58:26.760 --> 01:58:31.000
flanked by loving children
and the "kitchen deity."

01:58:31.000 --> 01:58:37.610
That's the opening
to Marilyn's --

01:58:37.610 --> 01:58:42.080
probably one of her most
well-known early poems

01:58:42.080 --> 01:58:48.070
"How I Got That Name: An
Essay on Assimilation".

01:58:48.070 --> 01:58:51.430
Marily's poetics were
an exuberant mix,

01:58:51.430 --> 01:58:56.280
an elegant strictness learned
from classical Chinese poetry,

01:58:56.280 --> 01:58:58.820
and also apprenticing at Iowa

01:58:58.820 --> 01:59:01.810
with Donald Justice,
and Jane Cooper.

01:59:01.810 --> 01:59:05.160
It is with Marilyn that
I most share aesthetics,

01:59:05.160 --> 01:59:09.280
although where she calls on
the formal to be reckless,

01:59:09.280 --> 01:59:12.070
I could do the opposite.

01:59:12.070 --> 01:59:15.200
The first time I
made the acquaintance

01:59:15.200 --> 01:59:19.670
of Marilyn's work was when
I was co-poetry editor

01:59:19.670 --> 01:59:22.400
at Bridge Magazine in Chinatown.

01:59:22.400 --> 01:59:26.180
I was also studying Japanese
at Columbia University,

01:59:26.180 --> 01:59:30.820
which did not lead to a PhD,
mainly because I couldn't focus

01:59:30.820 --> 01:59:33.210
on learning my congee.

01:59:33.210 --> 01:59:36.870
I had one foot on campus,
and the other in the streets

01:59:36.870 --> 01:59:40.280
or more literally at the
Hungarian Pastry Shop

01:59:40.280 --> 01:59:43.740
on Amsterdam Avenue,
which is still there!

01:59:43.740 --> 01:59:45.840
[Laughter] Where I'd sit
with a yellow legal pad

01:59:45.840 --> 01:59:48.130
and pen writing what
would become

01:59:48.130 --> 01:59:51.640
"Air Pocket" and "Earshot".

01:59:51.640 --> 01:59:55.090
Although I did not
become fluent in Japanese,

01:59:55.090 --> 02:00:00.530
I did begin on awareness that
my incipient poetics were a part

02:00:00.530 --> 02:00:02.490
of my body.

02:00:02.490 --> 02:00:08.750
Classical Japanese aesthetics as
much as William Carlos Williams.

02:00:08.750 --> 02:00:12.410
In fact, as an aside,
even my new work prompted

02:00:12.410 --> 02:00:18.240
by science abides by a Japanese
aesthetic, which I write

02:00:18.240 --> 02:00:23.150
about in Brain Fever,
in an essay.

02:00:23.150 --> 02:00:27.360
During this time too,
there were several growing

02:00:27.360 --> 02:00:29.850
political-cultural movements.

02:00:29.850 --> 02:00:34.710
Artists called against U.S.
intervention in Central America,

02:00:34.710 --> 02:00:39.730
anti-apartheid organizations and
several allied with organizing

02:00:39.730 --> 02:00:42.790
around issue about homelessness.

02:00:42.790 --> 02:00:47.330
We organized greetings,
publications, went to Nicaragua,

02:00:47.330 --> 02:00:51.700
danced, had babies,
looked for teaching jobs,

02:00:51.700 --> 02:00:55.840
hung out with Adrienne
Rich and June Jordan.

02:00:57.180 --> 02:01:02.450
Curating pushes one to widen
circles of people and aesthetics

02:01:02.450 --> 02:01:05.420
and that is just
were I found myself.

02:01:05.420 --> 02:01:10.070
When Basement Workshop shut its
doors, I open "Word of mouth",

02:01:10.070 --> 02:01:11.710
a series that found a home

02:01:11.710 --> 02:01:15.210
in the Chatham Square
Public Library.

02:01:15.210 --> 02:01:20.540
Curating allows one to meet
much admired writers, for me,

02:01:20.540 --> 02:01:24.790
I was pleased to have a full
house for Trinh T. Minh-ha,

02:01:24.790 --> 02:01:27.970
who was born in Hanoi in 1952.

02:01:27.970 --> 02:01:30.670
The innovative filmmaker
and poet

02:01:30.670 --> 02:01:35.820
who wrote the groundbreaking
book of theory, Woman, Native,

02:01:35.820 --> 02:01:40.970
Other: Writing post
coloniality and feminism.

02:01:49.590 --> 02:01:52.500
Also, my contemporary,
Cathy Song,

02:01:52.500 --> 02:01:59.210
one a 1992 yield younger
poet award for Picture Bride.

02:01:59.210 --> 02:02:02.050
Here are the closing
lines from a later poem:

02:02:02.050 --> 02:02:08.540
"Don't talk like you came
from the pineapple fields,

02:02:08.540 --> 02:02:11.180
meant we couldn't
tall with our mouths,

02:02:11.180 --> 02:02:16.010
full of broken sentences,
couldn't shove "yuh?"

02:02:16.010 --> 02:02:19.340
Like food heaped onto spoons.

02:02:19.340 --> 02:02:22.950
Don't talk like you just came
from the pineapple fields,

02:02:22.950 --> 02:02:25.840
meant we had to speak
proper English.

02:02:25.840 --> 02:02:29.720
We remained silent instead,
our tongues harnessed

02:02:29.720 --> 02:02:33.290
by the foreign shoelaces
of syntax,

02:02:33.290 --> 02:02:36.130
restrictive as the new
shoes Father brought home

02:02:36.130 --> 02:02:38.200
for us to wear.

02:02:38.200 --> 02:02:43.090
But, you may wonder,
"what happened

02:02:43.090 --> 02:02:46.470
to the whole roots
theme in my title?".

02:02:46.470 --> 02:02:51.290
You know, who knows
what the roots are,

02:02:51.290 --> 02:02:56.700
until someone has the courage to
dig or someone notices something

02:02:56.700 --> 02:02:59.720
that seems out of place".

02:02:59.720 --> 02:03:05.290
Back in 1991, the first
edition of Island was edited

02:03:05.290 --> 02:03:11.500
and translated by Him Lai,
Genny Lim and Judy Yung.

02:03:11.500 --> 02:03:14.030
This in exception
of the anthology,

02:03:14.030 --> 02:03:15.550
The Big Aiiieeeee [phonetic]!

02:03:15.550 --> 02:03:19.460
literally brought to life
both original Cantonese

02:03:19.460 --> 02:03:24.740
and translated poems that
were carved onto the walls

02:03:24.740 --> 02:03:30.810
of Angel Island Detention Center
by Chinese hoping to immigrate

02:03:30.810 --> 02:03:35.510
between 1910 and 1940.

02:03:35.510 --> 02:03:40.270
Here is one of the many
poems, wish we had more.

02:03:40.270 --> 02:03:49.340
From the book Island: "Instead
of remaining a citizen of China,

02:03:49.340 --> 02:03:51.690
I willingly became an ox.

02:03:51.690 --> 02:03:57.890
I intended to come to
America to earn a living.

02:03:57.890 --> 02:04:00.890
The Western styled
buildings are lofty;

02:04:00.890 --> 02:04:04.500
but I have not the
luck to live in them.

02:04:04.500 --> 02:04:10.100
How was anyone to know that
my dwelling place would be

02:04:10.100 --> 02:04:12.690
a prison?"

02:04:12.690 --> 02:04:16.350
Going back a few years
from the 1991 publication,

02:04:16.350 --> 02:04:23.270
in 1988 financial redress
was awarded to 82,000

02:04:23.270 --> 02:04:28.590
of the 120,000 detainees
of Japanese ancestry

02:04:28.590 --> 02:04:32.970
who had been incarcerated in
war time detention centers.

02:04:32.970 --> 02:04:36.420
They're followed a renewed
focus on those who struggled

02:04:36.420 --> 02:04:40.790
to survive and because
of what poetry can do,

02:04:40.790 --> 02:04:44.590
give song to protest and
passion, we have books

02:04:44.590 --> 02:04:48.660
such as Poets Behind
Barbed wire,

02:04:48.660 --> 02:04:55.360
here is one of the translated
poems: "Fifty and more

02:04:55.360 --> 02:04:59.860
of us prisoners gather
here to burn incense

02:04:59.860 --> 02:05:02.420
on an empty sardine can.

02:05:02.420 --> 02:05:05.920
For the repose of
a departed soul."

02:05:07.360 --> 02:05:13.030
These are poems that were
written in the detention centers

02:05:13.030 --> 02:05:15.670
and then later translated.

02:05:15.670 --> 02:05:25.650
Karen mentioned Yoshiko
Uchida, the memoir Desert Exile,

02:05:25.650 --> 02:05:28.940
in that memoir there are poems

02:05:28.940 --> 02:05:33.690
by her mother whose
pen name was Yukari:

02:05:33.690 --> 02:05:38.090
"Four months have passed,
and at last I learn

02:05:38.090 --> 02:05:42.880
to call this horse
stall my family's home".

02:05:52.580 --> 02:06:00.860
Rereading the work of Violet
Kazue de Cristoforo was surely

02:06:00.860 --> 02:06:04.700
one of the most exhilarant.

02:06:04.700 --> 02:06:09.560
I was stunned to
recognize a literary root

02:06:09.560 --> 02:06:14.980
that hadn't struck me when the
collection came out in 1991.

02:06:17.390 --> 02:06:20.240
Here is one of the pieces:

02:06:20.240 --> 02:06:28.730
"Strong sunrays barracks are
all low and dark, sun rays.

02:06:28.730 --> 02:06:31.930
The arrival of spring and
summer is typically late

02:06:31.930 --> 02:06:34.760
in the high plains of Tule Lake,

02:06:34.760 --> 02:06:37.900
the largest of the ten
internment camps built

02:06:37.900 --> 02:06:42.880
to house more than 18,000
detainees on about six miles

02:06:42.880 --> 02:06:45.990
of black volcanic ash.

02:06:45.990 --> 02:06:49.990
After the long, gloomy
winter days the intense glare

02:06:49.990 --> 02:06:54.380
of summer creates a strong
contrast and makes the low,

02:06:54.380 --> 02:06:58.180
dark, tar-papered barracks
seem even more dismal

02:06:58.180 --> 02:07:01.560
and disheartening
for the internees."

02:07:03.670 --> 02:07:12.970
The section in which
appears a Poetic Reflections

02:07:12.970 --> 02:07:16.790
of the Tule Lake
Internment Camp, 1944, sorry,

02:07:16.790 --> 02:07:21.880
this section appears
on this section

02:07:21.880 --> 02:07:25.110
of the [inaudible]
titled Poetic Reflections

02:07:25.110 --> 02:07:29.200
of the Tule Lake
Internment Camp, 1944.

02:07:29.200 --> 02:07:31.640
What may not be apparent
by this title is

02:07:31.640 --> 02:07:38.680
that poetic reflections are a
form in Japanese literature.

02:07:38.680 --> 02:07:42.810
You may know it as
Haibun, a mixed genre

02:07:42.810 --> 02:07:47.210
that typically combines
prose and Haiku.

02:07:47.210 --> 02:07:49.600
Here is another one
of her pieces.

02:07:49.600 --> 02:07:52.570
It's a little bit longer.

02:07:52.570 --> 02:07:57.620
So, we start with the Haiku
and it looks like a title

02:07:57.620 --> 02:08:02.530
but it's a Haiku:
"Flowers on Tule Reeds

02:08:02.530 --> 02:08:08.780
and Sandy Flats Brother
Confined over 200 Days,

02:08:08.780 --> 02:08:11.270
Brother's Imprisonment".

02:08:11.270 --> 02:08:17.370
The November 4, 1943, warehouse
incident, caused by reports

02:08:17.370 --> 02:08:19.950
of thefts of food
for the internees

02:08:19.950 --> 02:08:25.580
by War Relocation
Authority (WRA) personnel,

02:08:25.580 --> 02:08:31.010
resulted in confrontations
and disturbances at Tule Lake.

02:08:31.010 --> 02:08:35.230
Brother Tokyo, an innocent
bystander, had been asked

02:08:35.230 --> 02:08:38.960
to help restore order
among the agitators.

02:08:38.960 --> 02:08:42.100
As he was about to do
so, he was arrested

02:08:42.100 --> 02:08:46.340
by WRA Internal Security
Personnel and accused

02:08:46.340 --> 02:08:49.260
of taking part in the disorder.

02:08:49.260 --> 02:08:52.600
During a night of brutal
interrogation he was cruelly

02:08:52.600 --> 02:08:56.750
beaten and, not only was
he denied medical treatment

02:08:56.750 --> 02:09:01.590
for his injury, but he was
a prisoner in the "Bull Pen"

02:09:01.590 --> 02:09:06.010
of the camp stockade -- a
place for maximum punishment

02:09:06.010 --> 02:09:08.440
for serious offenders.

02:09:08.440 --> 02:09:13.740
Following the occurrence,
army troops took over control

02:09:13.740 --> 02:09:19.000
of the camp and martial law
was declared at Tule Lake.

02:09:19.000 --> 02:09:21.540
Then came spring,
the snow melted

02:09:21.540 --> 02:09:25.600
and the Tule leaves
sprouted and grew.

02:09:25.600 --> 02:09:29.280
By July the reeds
even had blossoms.

02:09:29.280 --> 02:09:33.470
Brother Tokio was still
confined in the 'Bull Pen'

02:09:33.470 --> 02:09:36.830
after nine months
of imprisonment

02:09:36.830 --> 02:09:39.830
without trial or a hearing.

02:09:39.830 --> 02:09:43.480
Fall was about to come again
and, under those conditions

02:09:43.480 --> 02:09:46.390
of dark uncertainty
and desperation,

02:09:46.390 --> 02:09:49.370
everything was measured
in terms of the growth

02:09:49.370 --> 02:09:52.720
and death of the Tule reeds."

02:09:52.720 --> 02:09:59.130
I have been writing in a
form known as the zuihitsu,

02:09:59.130 --> 02:10:00.970
a classical Japanese form

02:10:00.970 --> 02:10:05.150
that is neither poetry nor prose
although a piece can resemble

02:10:05.150 --> 02:10:07.340
either or a combination.

02:10:07.340 --> 02:10:11.160
Haibun, for example,
is considered zuihitsu.

02:10:11.160 --> 02:10:14.780
Also, Bash?'s The Narrow
Road to the Interior,

02:10:14.780 --> 02:10:18.310
which is a title I stole
for my collections.

02:10:18.310 --> 02:10:24.930
For me, to find a
writer, to rediscover her,

02:10:24.930 --> 02:10:27.700
who expressed herself
in this form,

02:10:27.700 --> 02:10:30.290
was a shock of recognition.

02:10:30.290 --> 02:10:33.810
Again, I feel deeply connected
to a literary heritage

02:10:33.810 --> 02:10:36.690
that includes cross genre work.

02:10:36.690 --> 02:10:40.680
I recognize this
foremother for what she is.

02:10:40.680 --> 02:10:44.260
A writer, a pioneer, and
an Asian American woman

02:10:44.260 --> 02:10:45.560
who defiantly gave her name

02:10:45.560 --> 02:10:52.530
as Violet Kazue Matsuda
de Cristoforo,

02:10:52.530 --> 02:10:57.930
formerly Kazue Matsuda,
Internee ID No.

02:10:57.930 --> 02:11:09.120
29001 I want to thank the
organizers for asking me,

02:11:09.120 --> 02:11:12.580
inviting me to write
this, this summer.

02:11:12.580 --> 02:11:15.300
Half over has been my workshop.

02:11:15.300 --> 02:11:21.830
Just as Juan Felipe continued in
the comment that I began with,

02:11:21.830 --> 02:11:24.460
society was our workshop,

02:11:24.460 --> 02:11:28.430
it is always our workshop
whether we write alone

02:11:28.430 --> 02:11:31.850
or whether we write out in
the open it is not possible

02:11:31.850 --> 02:11:36.190
without social combustion,
social change,

02:11:36.190 --> 02:11:40.130
social human beings with voices
and hearts, and struggles

02:11:40.130 --> 02:11:43.030
and conflicts and
happiness and joy and riding

02:11:43.030 --> 02:11:46.770
on horses in full regalia.

02:11:46.770 --> 02:11:51.590
In closing, I have
a gift for you,

02:11:51.590 --> 02:11:58.850
and you may have copies
of it, is a Cento.

02:12:00.750 --> 02:12:09.320
This is a form where you
swipe lines by other writers.

02:12:09.320 --> 02:12:15.400
I have taken a line from
every poet in the anthology,

02:12:15.400 --> 02:12:21.960
and it's all in the same order
of the anthology: "Angel Island:

02:12:21.960 --> 02:12:25.380
A Cento" Thank you poetry
magazine [laughter] --

02:12:26.440 --> 02:12:29.310
Angel Island: A Cento.

02:12:32.270 --> 02:12:40.210
"Let the walls hiss/and
smoke when/I return to shore.

02:12:40.210 --> 02:12:45.780
Someone is scolding a dog,
barking now for/decades --

02:12:45.780 --> 02:12:54.080
I don't have emotions right now,
I like that he expresses himself

02:12:54.080 --> 02:13:00.300
to me as a kind of
witness in transition --

02:13:00.300 --> 02:13:04.510
by "women," he meant
Arab and Muslim women.

02:13:04.510 --> 02:13:10.250
A cop arrested her, trapped her
in the back of the police van.

02:13:10.250 --> 02:13:13.630
-- hope wrapped in old
newspapers and thrown away

02:13:13.630 --> 02:13:18.620
like offal, cleaned from
a fish the size of a man.

02:13:18.620 --> 02:13:23.780
This place in which I dream the
new body, whole and abiding,

02:13:23.780 --> 02:13:26.780
all the girls go suzie.

02:13:26.780 --> 02:13:30.740
Dance is a body's
refusal to die --

02:13:30.740 --> 02:13:35.330
as foretold by the Muslim
woman from Hornachos,

02:13:35.330 --> 02:13:42.710
shutters over the eyes, (the
CD: Converge, Jane Doe).

02:13:42.710 --> 02:13:46.300
Once, I was afraid
of being changed.

02:13:46.300 --> 02:13:48.140
Now that is done.

02:13:48.140 --> 02:13:51.170
To be an artist, you
must not blunt your,

02:13:51.170 --> 02:13:54.040
troubling vision,
no matter how queer.

02:13:54.040 --> 02:13:59.130
[Speaking French],
where do we come from?

02:13:59.130 --> 02:14:01.990
When the rains arrive,
we should be delighted

02:14:01.990 --> 02:14:07.480
to be taken/in drowning,
in devotion.

02:14:07.480 --> 02:14:11.100
The car radio plays
its one song.

02:14:11.100 --> 02:14:14.920
The song, therefore,
is important.

02:14:14.920 --> 02:14:20.750
Where are we going, Wayne
Kaumualii [phonetic] Westlake?

02:14:20.750 --> 02:14:24.870
Can't they hear kalapani
in my voice --

02:14:24.870 --> 02:14:27.760
I am trying to be marvelous.

02:14:27.760 --> 02:14:32.020
Wow, wow, wow, wow, wow, ¡wow!

02:14:32.020 --> 02:14:38.530
The trick of the model
minority, walk away.

02:14:38.530 --> 02:14:42.500
I try to imitate them at home,
mira mamá, but my mother yells

02:14:42.500 --> 02:14:44.270
at me, says they
didn't come here

02:14:44.270 --> 02:14:47.070
so I could speak
some beggar language.

02:14:47.070 --> 02:14:50.640
Now that the hillbilly
whisper guides me which way

02:14:50.640 --> 02:14:55.570
to turn how far up the
turn is for the bird,

02:14:55.570 --> 02:14:57.830
everything hangs in the air.

02:14:57.830 --> 02:15:02.250
'Ay Dios', she exclaimed,
surrounded by photos,

02:15:02.250 --> 02:15:07.350
niños and nietos, where
I'm the only chino --

02:15:07.350 --> 02:15:12.410
You speak of a very good
sort of Englishness,

02:15:12.410 --> 02:15:15.690
who are you to mix up languages?

02:15:15.690 --> 02:15:22.760
Grouse, crow, craven,
or have in the past --

02:15:22.760 --> 02:15:25.600
His tongue tingled ripely.

02:15:25.600 --> 02:15:29.110
To make you a noun forever.

02:15:29.110 --> 02:15:32.180
A cunning rabbit
needs three holes,

02:15:32.180 --> 02:15:35.430
but I have never seen the field.

02:15:35.430 --> 02:15:38.090
All my life I hid in
the library reading

02:15:38.090 --> 02:15:42.060
about Greek heroes
smiting their enemies.

02:15:42.060 --> 02:15:44.040
Mother died a refugee,

02:15:44.040 --> 02:15:48.850
she thought the status
was a promise of return.

02:15:48.850 --> 02:15:55.110
Tonight, spring infuses
fall, and memory's wick --

02:15:55.110 --> 02:15:59.930
observatories rise above
the snow, militarized.

02:15:59.930 --> 02:16:03.240
I think I could wrap
my arms all the way

02:16:03.240 --> 02:16:10.090
around the 24,901 miles
circumferenced Earth.

02:16:10.090 --> 02:16:13.070
And circle and contain.

02:16:13.070 --> 02:16:17.990
I worry that when I love
him he will die too.

02:16:17.990 --> 02:16:22.590
The radio in the kitchen is
stuck in the year I was born.

02:16:22.590 --> 02:16:26.740
The capitals of the
world are burning."

02:16:26.740 --> 02:16:28.540
Thank you so much.

